 "control_id": "A.5.9",\n        "description_of_activities": "1. Review existing DLP solution architecture and identify all components (e.g., agents, servers, consoles, databases). 2. Develop a standardized naming convention and tagging strategy for all DLP components, incorporating unique identifiers. 3. Implement the naming convention across all existing DLP assets. 4. Update asset management database/CMDB with the new unique identifiers for DLP components. 5. Establish procedures for ensuring all new DLP deployments adhere to the unique identification standard. 6. Conduct an audit to verify consistent application of unique IDs.",\n        "necessary_resources": "1 Security Engineer (0.2 FTE), 1 System Administrator (0.1 FTE), Existing CMDB/Asset Management System, Documentation tools, ~$2,000 (for potential minor tooling/scripting).",\n        "implementation_priority": "CRITICAL",\n        "implementation_responsibility": "IT Security Team",\n        "proposed_start_date": "2026-02-03",\n        "proposed_completion_date": "2026-03-03",\n        "actual_start_date": null,\n        "actual_completion_date": null,\n        "risk_owner_comments": "",\n        "method_for_evaluation": "1. 100% of DLP solution components have unique identifiers as per the defined standard. 2. All DLP components are accurately recorded in the CMDB with their unique IDs. 3. Zero instances of new DLP deployments lacking unique identification in monthly audits.",\n        "status": "Planned",\n        "estimated_cost": "$2,000",\n        "estimated_duration_days": 28,\n        "expected_risk_reduction": "Improved visibility and manageability of DLP assets, reducing configuration errors and enhancing incident response capabilities. This will contribute to a moderate reduction in the likelihood of DLP misconfigurations leading to data leakage."\n      },\n      {\n        "action_id": "ACTION-2",\n        "risk_id": "RISK--Data-Leakage-Preven-2026-001",\n        "threat": "Delayed detection or complete failure to detect data leakage incidents due to lack of centralized logging and correlation.",\n        "control_gap": "DLP solution is not integrated with the Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system.",\n        "control_id": "A.8.15",\n        "description_of_activities": "1. Identify relevant DLP event logs and alerts for SIEM integration (e.g., policy violations, blocked transfers, agent status). 2. Configure DLP solution to forward logs to the SIEM via a secure, standardized protocol (e.g., Syslog, API). 3. Configure SIEM to ingest, parse, and normalize DLP logs. 4. Develop and implement SIEM correlation rules and dashboards specifically for DLP events to identify potential data leakage patterns. 5. Establish alert thresholds and incident response playbooks for critical DLP alerts within the SIEM. 6. Test the end-to-end integration, log flow, alert generation, and incident response procedures. 7. Train SOC analysts on DLP event monitoring and response within the SIEM.",\n        "necessary_resources": "2 Security Engineers (0.3 FTE each), SIEM platform licenses (if additional capacity needed, ~$5,000), DLP solution documentation, Network team support (0.1 FTE for firewall rules/network configuration), ~$7,500 (for potential SIEM rule development/consulting).",\n        "implementation_priority": "CRITICAL",\n        "implementation_responsibility": "IT Security Team",\n        "proposed_start_date": "2026-02-03",\n        "proposed_completion_date": "2026-03-17",\n        "actual_start_date": null,\n        "actual_completion_date": null,\n        "risk_owner_comments": "",\n        "method_for_evaluation": "1. 100% of critical DLP alerts are forwarded to the SIEM. 2. All DLP logs are successfully ingested, parsed, and normalized in the SIEM. 3. Critical DLP incidents are detected and alerted by the SIEM within 5 minutes of occurrence. 4. SOC analysts demonstrate proficiency in monitoring and responding to DLP events via the SIEM.",\n        "status": "Planned",\n        "estimated_cost": "$7,500",\n        "estimated_duration_days": 42,\n        "expected_risk_reduction": "Significantly enhanced detection and response capabilities for data leakage incidents, reducing the impact and likelihood of successful data exfiltration. This will lead to a high reduction in the overall residual risk associated with data leakage."\n      }\n    ],\n    "summary": {\n      "total_actions": 2,\n      "total_estimated_cost": "$9,500",\n      "total_duration_days": 42,\n      "expected_risk_rating_after": "Low",\n      "expected_residual_risk_after": "Low"\n    }\n  }\n}','\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1. 1. Review existing DLP solution architecture and identify all components (e.g., agents, servers, consoles, databases). 2. Develop a standardized naming convention and tagging strategy for all DLP components, incorporating unique identifiers. 3. Implement the naming convention across all existing DLP assets. 4. Update asset management database/CMDB with the new unique identifiers for DLP components. 5. Establish procedures for ensuring all new DLP deployments adhere to the unique identification standard. 6. Conduct an audit to verify consistent application of unique IDs. 2. 1. Identify relevant DLP event logs and alerts for SIEM integration (e.g., policy violations, blocked transfers, agent status). 2. Configure DLP solution to forward logs to the SIEM via a secure, standardized protocol (e.g., Syslog, API). 3. Configure SIEM to ingest, parse, and normalize DLP logs. 4. Develop and implement SIEM correlation rules and dashboards specifically for DLP events to identify potential data leakage patterns. 5. Establish alert thresholds and incident response playbooks for critical DLP alerts within the SIEM. 6. Test the end-to-end integration, log flow, alert generation, and incident response procedures. 7. Train SOC analysts on DLP event monitoring and response within the SIEM.','PENDING',NULL,NULL,'2026-01-27 17:30:46',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO risks VALUES(25,'RSK-025',' Data Leakage Prevention','Software Assets','Data Leakage Due to Outdated or Ineffective DLP Policies','Data Leakage Due to Outdated or Ineffective DLP Policies affecting  Data Leakage Prevention',3.0,'Medium',3.0,'Low','Low','Low',replace('[\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.8.12",\n    "control_name": "Data leakage prevention (Hybrid mode)",\n    "category": "Preventive",\n    "current_rating": 3,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Hybrid (some monitor, some block)''",\n    "effectiveness": "ADEQUATE"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.8.12",\n    "control_name": "Data leakage prevention (Policy types enforced)",\n    "category": "Preventive",\n    "current_rating": 4,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''File-based, User-based, Content-based'' policies actively enforced",\n    "effectiveness": "STRONG"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.5.1",\n    "control_name": "Policies for information security (DLP policy review)",\n    "category": "Preventive",\n    "current_rating": 3,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Annually'' DLP policies are reviewed and updated",\n    "effectiveness": "ADEQUATE"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.6.3",\n    "control_name": "Information security awareness, education and training",\n    "category": "Preventive",\n    "current_rating": 4,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Yes, mandatory and regular'' security awareness training provided",\n    "effectiveness": "STRONG"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.5.18",\n    "control_name": "Access rights management (DLP policy exceptions)",\n    "category": "Preventive",\n    "current_rating": 4,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Yes, a formal documented process'' for DLP policy exceptions",\n    "effectiveness": "STRONG"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.8.12",\n    "control_name": "Data leakage prevention (Hybrid mode)",\n    "category": "Detective",\n    "current_rating": 3,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Hybrid (some monitor, some block)''",\n    "effectiveness": "ADEQUATE"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.8.16",\n    "control_name": "Monitoring activities (DLP alerts 24/7)",\n    "category": "Detective",\n    "current_rating": 4,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Yes, 24/7'' DLP alerts actively monitored",\n    "effectiveness": "STRONG"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.5.26",\n    "control_name": "Incident management planning and preparation (DLP workflow)",\n    "category": "Corrective",\n    "current_rating": 3,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Yes'' there is a defined incident response workflow for DLP alerts",\n    "effectiveness": "ADEQUATE"\n  },\n  {\n    "control_id": "A.8.16",\n    "control_name": "Monitoring activities (DLP false positive management)",\n    "category": "Corrective",\n    "current_rating": 2,\n    "source": "Questionnaire",\n    "evidence": "User confirmed: ''Yes, informally managed'' process for false positives",\n    "effectiveness": "LIMITED"\n  }\n]','\n',char(10)),2.49000000000000021,0.510000000000000008,'Unknown',replace('[\n  {\n    "gap_description": "Monitoring activities (DLP false positive management) is weak/deficient (rated 2/5)",\n    "control_id": "A.8.16",\n    "current_rating": 2,\n    "evidence": "Low effectiveness rating",\n    "impact": "Insufficient protection - control effectiveness only 2/5",\n    "severity": "MEDIUM"\n  }\n]','\n',char(10)),replace('[\n  {\n    "gap_description": "Monitoring activities (DLP false positive management) is weak/deficient (rated 2/5)",\n    "control_id": "A.8.16",\n    "current_rating": 2,\n    "evidence": "Low effectiveness rating",\n    "impact": "Insufficient protection - control effectiveness only 2/5",\n    "severity": "MEDIUM"\n  }\n]','\n',char(10)),NULL,NULL,'ACCEPT','Suresh','Medium','2026-03-10','Open','2026-01-27','2026-01-27',NULL,NULL,NULL,replace('{\n  "discovery_summary": {\n    "cia_methodology": "CIA (Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability)",\n    "cia_rating_scale": "4-level: Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, Extreme",\n    "cia_definitions_source": "Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx, Sheet: Asset Inventorization Guideline",\n    "business_value_calculation_method": "Asset Value Chart (lookup table combining concatenated CIA ratings)",\n    "business_value_levels": [\n      "Very Low",\n      "Low",\n      "Medium",\n      "High",\n      "Very High"\n    ],\n    "business_value_source": "Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx, Sheet: Asset Inventory",\n    "criticality_classification_method": "Business Value to Criticality Mapping (Criticality Classification Table)",\n    "criticality_levels": [\n      "Insignificant",\n      "Low Critical",\n      "Medium Critical",\n      "High Critical",\n      "Very High Critical"\n    ],\n    "criticality_source": "Asset Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 4; Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx, Sheet: Asset Inventorization Guideline",\n    "searches_performed": [\n      "impact assessment methodology",\n      "CIA impact rating scale and definitions",\n      "Asset Business Value calculation from CIA impact ratings"\n    ]\n  },\n  "threat_analysis": [\n    {\n      "threat_id": "threat_1",\n      "threat_name": "Compromise of DLP System Leading to Undetected Data Exfiltration",\n      "threat_description": "An advanced persistent threat (APT) or malicious insider could exploit a vulnerability in the Forcepoint DLP solution (version 16.0) or its underlying infrastructure, or compromise administrative credentials, to gain unauthorized access. Due to the lack of integration with a SIEM system, these sophisticated bypass attempts or internal policy modifications within the critical DLP solution would not be correlated with other security events, significantly delaying detection. An informally managed false positive process could further desensitize the 24/7 security team, allowing an attacker to exfiltrate sensitive PII and Legal Documents across the network, data at rest, or endpoints without triggering effective alerts or blocks, resulting in a major data breach.",\n      "impact_assessment": {\n        "confidentiality": {\n          "rating": "Extreme",\n          "numeric_value": 4,\n          "reasoning": "Based on questionnaire answer [3. DLP Solution Details and Configuration Facts] stating [''PII (Personally Identifiable Information)'', ''Legal Documents''] are protected, and the contextual description indicating ''undetected data exfiltration'' and a ''major data breach'' of these sensitive types. This meets the discovered definition for ''Extreme'': ''Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization would cause serious damage to the interests of the organization. Disclosure within the organization will be strictly on a \u2018need-to-know\u2019 basis.''"\n        },\n        "integrity": {\n          "rating": "Extreme",\n          "numeric_value": 4,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description mentioning ''internal policy modifications within the critical DLP solution would not be correlated with other security events'', implying potential for unauthorized modification of DLP policies. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), such modifications would have a ''severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations'' by undermining data protection. This meets the discovered definition for ''Extreme'': ''Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        },\n        "availability": {\n          "rating": "Serious",\n          "numeric_value": 3,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description focusing on ''undetected data exfiltration'' due to bypass, rather than outright system shutdown. While the system remains operational, its core function of preventing data leakage is severely compromised, making it effectively unavailable for its intended purpose. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), this functional unavailability would have a ''serious adverse effect on business operations''. This meets the discovered definition for ''Serious'': ''Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have a serious adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        }\n      },\n      "overall_impact_calculation": {\n        "confidentiality_numeric": 4,\n        "integrity_numeric": 4,\n        "availability_numeric": 3,\n        "calculation_method": "max(C, I, A)",\n        "calculation": "max(4, 4, 3) = 4",\n        "overall_impact": "4 - Extreme",\n        "overall_impact_numeric": 4\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      "threat_id": "threat_2",\n      "threat_name": "Data Leakage Due to Outdated or Ineffective DLP Policies",\n      "threat_description": "The Forcepoint DLP policies, which are critical for protecting PII and Legal Documents across network, data at rest, and endpoints, are reviewed only annually. This infrequent review cycle creates a significant vulnerability where new data types, communication channels, or evolving regulatory requirements may not be adequately covered by existing policies. For instance, the adoption of a new collaboration tool or cloud service could create an unmonitored channel for data exfiltration. Furthermore, the ''informally managed'' false positive process could lead to policies being overly relaxed to reduce alert noise, inadvertently creating loopholes that allow sensitive data to bypass DLP controls, especially for data covered by ''monitor-only'' policies, leading to unintentional data leakage.",\n      "impact_assessment": {\n        "confidentiality": {\n          "rating": "Extreme",\n          "numeric_value": 4,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description stating ''unintentional data leakage'' of ''PII and Legal Documents'' and the risk statement mentioning ''regulatory non-compliance, financial penalties, and loss of customer trust''. This directly aligns with the ''Extreme'' definition: ''Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization would cause serious damage to the interests of the organization. Disclosure within the organization will be strictly on a \u2018need-to-know\u2019 basis.''"\n        },\n        "integrity": {\n          "rating": "Serious",\n          "numeric_value": 3,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the threat of ''outdated or ineffective DLP policies'' leading to data leakage. While not direct data modification, the failure of policies to adequately protect data means the integrity of the data''s protected state is compromised. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), this failure would have a ''serious adverse effect on business operations''. This meets the discovered definition for ''Serious'': ''Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have a serious adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        },\n        "availability": {\n          "rating": "Moderate",\n          "numeric_value": 2,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the threat focusing on policy effectiveness rather than the availability of the DLP system itself. The system would still be accessible and running, but its protective function is diminished. This is a moderate adverse effect on the availability of effective protection, not the system itself. This meets the discovered definition for ''Moderate'': ''Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have a moderate adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        }\n      },\n      "overall_impact_calculation": {\n        "confidentiality_numeric": 4,\n        "integrity_numeric": 3,\n        "availability_numeric": 2,\n        "calculation_method": "max(C, I, A)",\n        "calculation": "max(4, 3, 2) = 4",\n        "overall_impact": "4 - Extreme",\n        "overall_impact_numeric": 4\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      "threat_id": "threat_3",\n      "threat_name": "Malicious or Negligent Insider Bypassing DLP Controls",\n      "threat_description": "A malicious insider or a negligent user, potentially with administrative access or a deep understanding of the Forcepoint DLP (version 16.0) configuration and operational procedures, could intentionally or unintentionally bypass existing controls. The ''informally managed'' false positive process could be exploited by an insider to generate excessive noise, making it harder for the 24/7 security team to identify genuine data exfiltration attempts of PII and Legal Documents. While security awareness training is mandatory, an insider could leverage knowledge of the annual policy review cycle to exploit temporary gaps in policy coverage, or use the ''monitor-only'' policy modes to exfiltrate sensitive data via network, data at rest, or endpoint channels, leading to an insider-driven data breach.",\n      "impact_assessment": {\n        "confidentiality": {\n          "rating": "Extreme",\n          "numeric_value": 4,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description stating ''insider-driven data breach of PII and Legal Documents'' and the risk statement mentioning ''severe regulatory fines, legal liabilities, and reputational damage''. This directly aligns with the ''Extreme'' definition: ''Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization would cause serious damage to the interests of the organization. Disclosure within the organization will be strictly on a \u2018need-to-know\u2019 basis.''"\n        },\n        "integrity": {\n          "rating": "Extreme",\n          "numeric_value": 4,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the threat involving an insider ''bypassing DLP controls'' and exploiting ''Forcepoint DLP configuration weaknesses''. This implies a direct compromise of the integrity of the DLP system''s protective mechanisms, potentially through unauthorized modification of policies or data. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), this would have a ''severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations''. This meets the discovered definition for ''Extreme'': ''Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        },\n        "availability": {\n          "rating": "Moderate",\n          "numeric_value": 2,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the threat focusing on bypassing controls and exfiltrating data, not on making the DLP system unavailable. The system would still be accessible and running, but its protective function is circumvented. This is a moderate adverse effect on the availability of effective protection, not the system itself. This meets the discovered definition for ''Moderate'': ''Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have a moderate adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        }\n      },\n      "overall_impact_calculation": {\n        "confidentiality_numeric": 4,\n        "integrity_numeric": 4,\n        "availability_numeric": 2,\n        "calculation_method": "max(C, I, A)",\n        "calculation": "max(4, 4, 2) = 4",\n        "overall_impact": "4 - Extreme",\n        "overall_impact_numeric": 4\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      "threat_id": "threat_4",\n      "threat_name": "Delayed Incident Response and Inefficient Management Due to Lack of Unique Asset ID",\n      "threat_description": "The critical Forcepoint DLP solution (version 16.0), responsible for protecting PII and Legal Documents, lacks a unique identifier or asset ID. In the event of a security incident, a critical vulnerability discovery, or a system outage affecting the DLP, the absence of a clear, unique identifier will significantly hinder efficient incident response, troubleshooting, and asset management processes. This could lead to delays in identifying the specific instance of the DLP system, correlating it with other security tools (especially without SIEM integration), applying patches, or initiating recovery procedures. Such delays would prolong the organization''s exposure to data leakage risks and impact the availability and integrity of the DLP service, which is critical to business operations.",\n      "impact_assessment": {\n        "confidentiality": {\n          "rating": "Serious",\n          "numeric_value": 3,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description stating that the lack of an asset ID ''would prolong the organization''s exposure to data leakage risks''. While not a direct cause of disclosure, it significantly increases the window and potential scale of a breach if one occurs. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), this prolonged exposure could lead to ''significant harm''. This meets the discovered definition for ''Serious'': ''Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization would cause significant harm to the interest of the organization.''"\n        },\n        "integrity": {\n          "rating": "Serious",\n          "numeric_value": 3,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description stating that delays in ''applying patches, or initiating recovery procedures'' and ''inefficient management'' could ''impact the availability and integrity of the DLP service''. This means the DLP system itself could operate in a compromised or unpatched state for longer, affecting its ability to maintain data integrity. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), this would have a ''serious adverse effect on business operations''. This meets the discovered definition for ''Serious'': ''Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have a serious adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        },\n        "availability": {\n          "rating": "Extreme",\n          "numeric_value": 4,\n          "reasoning": "Based on the contextual description stating that the lack of an asset ID ''will significantly hinder efficient incident response, troubleshooting... and recovery procedures'' and ''impacts the availability... of the DLP service''. The risk statement mentions ''operational disruptions''. Given the ''High'' criticality of the DLP solution (Fact: [2. Business Context and Scope]), prolonged unavailability or inability to recover would have a ''severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations''. This meets the discovered definition for ''Extreme'': ''Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations.''"\n        }\n      },\n      "overall_impact_calculation": {\n        "confidentiality_numeric": 3,\n        "integrity_numeric": 3,\n        "availability_numeric": 4,\n        "calculation_method": "max(C, I, A)",\n        "calculation": "max(3, 3, 4) = 4",\n        "overall_impact": "4 - Extreme",\n        "overall_impact_numeric": 4\n      }\n    }\n  ],\n  "asset_cia_ratings": {\n    "confidentiality": {\n      "rating": "Extreme",\n      "numeric_value": 4,\n      "reasoning": "Asset-level CIA: Maximum C value across all threats. Threat 1: Extreme(4), Threat 2: Extreme(4), Threat 3: Extreme(4), Threat 4: Serious(3) \u2192 Asset C = Extreme(4)",\n      "threat_breakdown": [\n        "Threat 1: Extreme(4)",\n        "Threat 2: Extreme(4)",\n        "Threat 3: Extreme(4)",\n        "Thr