", "comments_additional_notes": "Controls implemented successfully. Risk reduced significantly.\n", "asset_product_owner_confirmation_name": "John Smith"}, "summary": {"implementation_status": "Yes", "controls_effective": "Yes", "completion_percentage": 80.0}}, {"followup_date": "2026-01-21 15:21:59", "decision_type": "TREAT", "questionnaire_type": "TREAT Follow-up", "answers": {"action_owner": "John Smith", "mitigation_actions_implemented": "Yes", "controls_operating_effectively": "Yes", "likelihood_impact_reduced": "Yes", "additional_treatment_required": "No", "evidence_available": "Yes", "expected_residual_risk": "Low", "completion_percentage": 80, "expected_completion_date": "2026-03-15", "reason_for_delay": "No delays", "comments_additional_notes": "Controls implemented successfully. Risk reduced significantly.\n", "asset_product_owner_confirmation_name": "John Smith"}, "summary": {"implementation_status": "Yes", "controls_effective": "Yes", "completion_percentage": 80.0}}, {"followup_date": "2026-01-21 15:31:09", "decision_type": "TREAT", "questionnaire_type": "TREAT Follow-up", "answers": {"action_owner": "John Smith", "mitigation_actions_implemented": "Yes", "controls_operating_effectively": "Yes", "likelihood_impact_reduced": "Yes", "additional_treatment_required": "No", "evidence_available": "Yes", "expected_residual_risk": "Low", "completion_percentage": 80, "expected_completion_date": "2026-03-15", "reason_for_delay": "No delays", "comments_additional_notes": "Controls implemented successfully. Risk reduced significantly.\n", "asset_product_owner_confirmation_name": "John Smith"}, "summary": {"implementation_status": "Yes", "controls_effective": "Yes", "completion_percentage": 80.0}}]','2026-01-28 07:27:57','2026-01-28 07:28:56',1);
INSERT INTO questionnaire_templates VALUES(7,'AGENT0','Office Building','{"questionnaire_title": "Risk Assessment Questionnaire for Office Building", "asset_type_analyzed": "Office Building", "intelligence_summary": {"asset_understanding": "An Office Building is a physical asset that provides workspace and houses personnel, information assets (e.g., documents, servers, network infrastructure), and other critical equipment. Its risks are primarily physical, environmental, and operational, impacting business continuity, safety, and the security of assets and data contained within.", "key_risk_factors": ["Physical access controls (e.g., badge systems, guards)", "Security monitoring (e.g., surveillance cameras, 24/7 monitoring)", "Environmental controls (e.g., fire suppression, flood prevention)", "Occupancy and criticality of personnel/functions housed", "Dependency on utilities (power, water, internet) and their redundancy", "Emergency preparedness and response capabilities", "Location-specific risks (e.g., natural disaster zones)", "Types of sensitive assets or operations conducted within the building"], "methodology_discovered": "The organization uses a structured risk management framework involving risk identification, assessment (calculating Risk Value = Risk Impact * Risk Probability), treatment, acceptance, and monitoring. It defines criteria for performing assessments and acceptance. CIA impact ratings are used internally by analysts to determine Asset Business Value, not directly by asset owners.", "scales_discovered": "Overall Impact Rating (RI Value): 1=Very Low, 2=Low, 3=Medium, 4=High, 5=Very High. Overall Probability Rating (RP Value): 1=Very Low (Greater than one year), 2=Low (Once every year), 3=Medium (Once every 4-6 months), 4=High (Once every 1-3 months), 5=Very High (more than once per month). Asset Criticality Classification: Insignificant, Low Critical, Medium Critical, High Critical, Very high Critical.", "why_these_questions": "These questions are designed to collect factual information about the Office Building''s characteristics, security measures, operational context, and the asset owner''s overall perspective on potential impact and likelihood. This factual data is crucial for subsequent analysis by Agents 1 (CIA impact), 2 (risk quantification), and 3 (control effectiveness). Asking for overall opinions leverages the owner''s business insight without requiring them to perform technical risk analysis or detailed CIA breakdowns, which are the responsibilities of the specialized agents.", "searches_performed": ["asset inventory structure, asset identification fields, asset type categories, risk assessment methodology, rating scales, control frameworks, terminology"]}, "sections": [{"section_name": "1. Asset Identification", "section_purpose": "To uniquely identify the Office Building within the organization''s asset inventory.", "questions": [{"question_id": "Q_ASSET_NAME", "question_text": "What is the specific name or title of this Office Building?", "question_type": "text", "required": true, "help_text": "e.g., Main Headquarters Building, Branch Office - Downtown, Warehouse & Office Facility - North", "why_this_matters": "Provides a unique identifier for the asset, crucial for tracking and reporting."}, {"question_id": "Q_ASSET_TYPE", "question_text": "What type of asset is this?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "PHYSICAL ASSETS", "label": "PHYSICAL ASSETS"}, {"value": "SOFTWARE ASSETS", "label": "SOFTWARE ASSETS"}, {"value": "INFORMATION ASSETS", "label": "INFORMATION ASSETS"}, {"value": "SERVICE ASSETS", "label": "SERVICE ASSETS"}, {"value": "PEOPLE ASSETS", "label": "PEOPLE ASSETS"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Select the primary category that best describes this asset.", "why_this_matters": "Classifies the asset according to organizational standards, guiding the appropriate risk assessment methodology."}, {"question_id": "Q_ASSET_CLASS_OWNER", "question_text": "Who is the Asset Class Owner for this Office Building?", "question_type": "text", "required": true, "help_text": "Provide the name or department responsible for the overall management and security of this building.", "why_this_matters": "Identifies the primary stakeholder accountable for the asset and its associated risks."}, {"question_id": "Q_ASSET_CUSTODIAN", "question_text": "Who is the Asset Custodian for this Office Building?", "question_type": "text", "required": false, "help_text": "Provide the name or department to whom the building is physically allocated for maintenance and day-to-day operations.", "why_this_matters": "Identifies the party responsible for the physical upkeep and immediate operational control of the asset."}, {"question_id": "Q_ASSET_LOCATION", "question_text": "What is the physical address or specific location of this Office Building?", "question_type": "text", "required": true, "help_text": "e.g., 123 Main Street, Anytown, State, Zip Code", "why_this_matters": "Crucial for identifying location-specific risks (e.g., natural disasters, local crime rates) and for emergency response."}, {"question_id": "Q_ASSET_DESCRIPTION", "question_text": "Provide a brief description of the Office Building and its primary purpose.", "question_type": "textarea", "required": false, "help_text": "e.g., ''A multi-story building housing corporate administrative functions, IT data center, and executive offices.''", "why_this_matters": "Provides context for the building''s role and helps understand the scope of potential impacts."}]}, {"section_name": "2. Business Context and Criticality", "section_purpose": "To understand the business importance and operational context of the Office Building.", "questions": [{"question_id": "Q_BUSINESS_CRITICALITY", "question_text": "What is the overall Asset Criticality Classification of this Office Building to the organization''s operations?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Insignificant", "label": "Insignificant - Very low impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised"}, {"value": "Low Critical", "label": "Low Critical - Low impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised"}, {"value": "Medium Critical", "label": "Medium Critical - Medium impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised"}, {"value": "High Critical", "label": "High Critical - High impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised"}, {"value": "Very high Critical", "label": "Very high Critical - Very high impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Consider the overall impact on business if the building''s confidentiality, integrity, and availability were compromised.", "why_this_matters": "Provides a high-level understanding of the asset''s importance, guiding the prioritization of risk assessment efforts."}, {"question_id": "Q_OCCUPANCY_COUNT", "question_text": "Approximately how many personnel (employees, contractors, visitors) occupy or regularly use this Office Building?", "question_type": "number", "required": true, "help_text": "Provide an average or maximum number of people present during operational hours.", "why_this_matters": "Indicates the potential impact on human safety and business continuity in case of an incident."}, {"question_id": "Q_CRITICAL_FUNCTIONS_HOUSED", "question_text": "Does this Office Building house any critical business functions or departments (e.g., data center, executive offices, primary call center)?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes", "label": "Yes"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Select ''Yes'' if essential operations that cannot be easily relocated are performed here.", "why_this_matters": "Highlights specific areas of high business impact if the building is compromised or unavailable."}, {"question_id": "Q_CRITICAL_FUNCTIONS_LIST", "question_text": "If ''Yes'' to the above, please list the critical business functions or departments housed within this building.", "question_type": "textarea", "required": false, "help_text": "e.g., ''Primary IT Data Center, Finance Department, Executive Leadership, Customer Support Call Center''", "why_this_matters": "Provides specific details on critical dependencies, aiding in impact analysis."}, {"question_id": "Q_DEPENDENT_BUSINESS_PROCESSES", "question_text": "Which key business processes are directly dependent on the continuous operation of this Office Building?", "question_type": "textarea", "required": false, "help_text": "e.g., ''Daily administrative operations, IT service delivery, customer support, product development''", "why_this_matters": "Helps identify the scope of business disruption if the building becomes unavailable."}]}, {"section_name": "3. Physical Security and Environmental Facts", "section_purpose": "To collect factual information about the physical security measures and environmental controls in place.", "questions": [{"question_id": "Q_PHYSICAL_ACCESS_CONTROLS", "question_text": "What primary physical access control systems are in place for the building perimeter and critical internal areas?", "question_type": "multiselect", "options": [{"value": "Badge System (RFID/Proximity)", "label": "Badge System (RFID/Proximity)"}, {"value": "Biometric Scanners", "label": "Biometric Scanners"}, {"value": "Key Locks", "label": "Key Locks"}, {"value": "Security Guards (24/7)", "label": "Security Guards (24/7)"}, {"value": "Security Guards (Business Hours)", "label": "Security Guards (Business Hours)"}, {"value": "Mantraps/Security Turnstiles", "label": "Mantraps/Security Turnstiles"}, {"value": "None", "label": "None"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Select all applicable access control mechanisms.", "why_this_matters": "Provides facts about controls preventing unauthorized physical access, impacting confidentiality and integrity of assets within."}, {"question_id": "Q_SURVEILLANCE_CAMERAS", "question_text": "Are surveillance cameras (CCTV) installed and actively monitored within and around the Office Building?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes, 24/7 monitored", "label": "Yes, 24/7 monitored"}, {"value": "Yes, periodically reviewed", "label": "Yes, periodically reviewed"}, {"value": "Yes, but not actively monitored", "label": "Yes, but not actively monitored"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Indicate the level of monitoring for surveillance systems.", "why_this_matters": "Fact about detective controls for physical security incidents, aiding in incident response and forensics."}, {"question_id": "Q_ALARM_SYSTEMS", "question_text": "Are alarm systems (e.g., intrusion detection, motion sensors) installed and monitored?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes, centrally monitored", "label": "Yes, centrally monitored"}, {"value": "Yes, local alarms only", "label": "Yes, local alarms only"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Specify if alarms are connected to a central monitoring station or are local only.", "why_this_matters": "Fact about detective controls for unauthorized entry, contributing to the overall security posture."}, {"question_id": "Q_FIRE_SUPPRESSION_SYSTEM", "question_text": "What type of fire detection and suppression systems are installed in the building?", "question_type": "multiselect", "options": [{"value": "Smoke Detectors", "label": "Smoke Detectors"}, {"value": "Heat Detectors", "label": "Heat Detectors"}, {"value": "Automatic Sprinkler System (Wet Pipe)", "label": "Automatic Sprinkler System (Wet Pipe)"}, {"value": "Automatic Sprinkler System (Dry Pipe)", "label": "Automatic Sprinkler System (Dry Pipe)"}, {"value": "Gas Suppression System (e.g., FM-200, Novec 1230) in critical areas", "label": "Gas Suppression System (e.g., FM-200, Novec 1230) in critical areas"}, {"value": "Fire Extinguishers", "label": "Fire Extinguishers"}, {"value": "None", "label": "None"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Select all applicable fire safety systems.", "why_this_matters": "Facts about controls mitigating fire risks, directly impacting availability and safety."}, {"question_id": "Q_UTILITY_REDUNDANCY", "question_text": "Are there redundant power sources (e.g., UPS, generators) or internet connectivity options for critical operations within the building?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes, for both power and internet", "label": "Yes, for both power and internet"}, {"value": "Yes, for power only", "label": "Yes, for power only"}, {"value": "Yes, for internet only", "label": "Yes, for internet only"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Indicate if backup systems are in place for essential utilities.", "why_this_matters": "Facts about controls ensuring availability of critical services, reducing downtime risk."}, {"question_id": "Q_ENVIRONMENTAL_RISKS", "question_text": "Is the Office Building located in an area prone to specific environmental risks (e.g., flood zone, seismic activity, severe weather)?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes", "label": "Yes"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}, {"value": "Unsure", "label": "Unsure"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Consider local geographical and meteorological conditions.", "why_this_matters": "Identifies external threat factors that could impact the building''s availability and integrity."}, {"question_id": "Q_ENVIRONMENTAL_RISKS_DETAILS", "question_text": "If ''Yes'' to the above, please specify the environmental risks.", "question_type": "textarea", "required": false, "help_text": "e.g., ''Located in a 100-year flood plain, high seismic activity zone, frequent hurricanes''", "why_this_matters": "Provides specific details for assessing the likelihood and potential impact of natural disasters."}]}, {"section_name": "4. Emergency Preparedness and Operational Controls", "section_purpose": "To gather facts about the building''s readiness for emergencies and operational security measures.", "questions": [{"question_id": "Q_EMERGENCY_EVACUATION_PLAN", "question_text": "Is there a documented and regularly practiced emergency evacuation plan for the Office Building?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes, regularly practiced", "label": "Yes, regularly practiced"}, {"value": "Yes, documented but not regularly practiced", "label": "Yes, documented but not regularly practiced"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Indicate if the plan is not only documented but also tested.", "why_this_matters": "Fact about a control for personnel safety and orderly response during emergencies, impacting human safety and business continuity."}, {"question_id": "Q_DISASTER_RECOVERY_PLAN", "question_text": "Is there a disaster recovery or business continuity plan specifically addressing the unavailability of this Office Building?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes, tested and maintained", "label": "Yes, tested and maintained"}, {"value": "Yes, documented but not tested", "label": "Yes, documented but not tested"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Indicate if a plan exists to continue operations if the building is unusable.", "why_this_matters": "Fact about a control for business continuity, directly impacting the availability of services and operations."}, {"question_id": "Q_INCIDENT_RESPONSE_PLAN", "question_text": "Is there an incident response plan for physical security incidents (e.g., unauthorized entry, theft, vandalism) specific to this building?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes, documented and practiced", "label": "Yes, documented and practiced"}, {"value": "Yes, documented but not practiced", "label": "Yes, documented but not practiced"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Indicate if a plan exists to respond to physical security breaches.", "why_this_matters": "Fact about a control for managing and mitigating the impact of physical security incidents."}, {"question_id": "Q_ASSET_INVENTORY_PHYSICAL", "question_text": "Is there a current and accurate inventory of critical physical assets (e.g., servers, specialized equipment, sensitive documents) housed within this building?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "Yes", "label": "Yes"}, {"value": "No", "label": "No"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Refers to an inventory of physical items, not just the building itself.", "why_this_matters": "Fact about an administrative control that helps in asset tracking, recovery, and impact assessment during an incident."}]}, {"section_name": "5. Overall Risk Perspective", "section_purpose": "To gather the asset owner''s overall qualitative assessment of potential impact and likelihood, without requiring technical risk analysis.", "questions": [{"question_id": "Q_OVERALL_IMPACT_RATING", "question_text": "Considering all identified risks and existing controls, what is the estimated overall ''Impact Rating'' if this Office Building were to be severely compromised (e.g., prolonged unavailability, major physical damage, significant security breach)?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "1", "label": "1 - Very Low: Risk has negligible impact on business and operations"}, {"value": "2", "label": "2 - Low: Risk does not have significant impact on business and operations"}, {"value": "3", "label": "3 - Medium: Risk has minimum impact on business and operations"}, {"value": "4", "label": "4 - High: Risk has serious impact on business and operations"}, {"value": "5", "label": "5 - Very High: Risk has catastrophic impact on business and operations"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Rate the overall business impact using the organization''s scale (1-5). This is your overall business judgment, not a technical calculation.", "why_this_matters": "Collects the asset owner''s high-level business perspective on potential harm, which is a critical input for Agent 2''s risk quantification."}, {"question_id": "Q_OVERALL_PROBABILITY_RATING", "question_text": "Considering all identified threats and vulnerabilities, what is the estimated ''Probability Rating'' of a severe compromise occurring to this Office Building within the next year?", "question_type": "dropdown", "options": [{"value": "1", "label": "1 - Very Low: Greater than one year"}, {"value": "2", "label": "2 - Low: Once every year"}, {"value": "3", "label": "3 - Medium: Once every 4-6 months"}, {"value": "4", "label": "4 - High: Once every 1-3 months"}, {"value": "5", "label": "5 - Very High: More than once per month"}], "required": true, "help_text": "Rate the overall likelihood using the organization''s scale (1-5). This is your overall business judgment, not a technical calculation.", "why_this_matters": "Collects the asset owner''s high-level business perspective on the likelihood of an adverse event, which is a critical input for Agent 2''s risk quantification."}]}]}','2026-01-29 11:25:30','2026-01-29 11:25:30',0);
CREATE TABLE rag_cache (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    query_hash TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    query_text TEXT NOT NULL,
    cached_result TEXT NOT NULL,
    created_date TEXT DEFAULT (datetime('now')),
    last_used TEXT DEFAULT (datetime('now')),
    hit_count INTEGER DEFAULT 0
);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(1,'cc537480afa9803387c4f4b49fb57872','What impact assessment methodology is used? CIA? DREAD? Custom?','"The organization uses a **custom** impact assessment methodology. It is not identified as \"CIA\" or \"DREAD\".\n\nThe methodology quantifies risk impact as a numerical quantity on a relative scale, independent of probability, with specific definitions for each category. This impact value is then used in conjunction with risk probability to derive an overall risk value. While the concept of Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability (CIA) is considered when developing the consequence criteria for impact, it is part of the custom framework rather than being the name of the methodology itself.\n\nHere are the details from the provided documents:\n\n**1. Identification and Quantification of Risk Impact:**\n\n*   **Process Step:** The Risk Management Procedure includes a task to \"Identify risk impact (consequences) if vulnerability is exploited.\"\n    *   **Document:** `Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx`, Table 3, \"Risk Assessment\" section.\n*   **Definition:** \"Impact shall be quantified as a numerical quantity to reflect damage if a given threat successfully exploits an associated vulnerability. Risk impact value rates the seriousness of a given risk on a relative scale, independent of its probability.\"\n    *   **Document:** `Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx`, Section 4.4.5 \"Identify the Risk Impact\".\n*   **Scale for Estimation:** The organization uses the following scale to estimate Risk Impact:\n    *   **Document:** `Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx`, Section 4.5.2 \"Risk Impact Evaluation (Compute the RI Value)\" and Table 4.\n\n    **TABLE: Risk Impact Evaluation Scale**\n    \n    Impact Category | Impact Definition                                                | Impact Rating\n    \n    Very Low        | Risk has negligible impact on business and operations            | 1            \n    Low             | Risk does not have significant impact on business and operations | 2            \n    Medium          | Risk has minimum impact on business and operations               | 3            \n    High            | Risk has serious impact on business and operations               | 4            \n    Very High       | Risk has catastrophic impact on business and operations          | 5            \n    \n\n**2. Considerations for Consequence (Impact) Criteria:**\n\nWhen defining consequence criteria (which informs the impact assessment), the organization considers the \"extent of damage or loss, or harm to an organization or individual resulting from the loss of confidentiality, integrity and availability of information.\"\nFactors explicitly considered for consequence criteria include:\n*   Loss of life or harm to individuals or groups\n*   Loss of freedom, dignity or right to privacy\n*   Loss of staff and intellectual capital (skills and expertise)\n*   Impaired internal or third-party operations (e.g., damage to a business function or process)\n*   Effects to plans and deadlines\n*   Loss of business and financial value\n*   Loss of business advantage or market share\n*   Damage to public trust or reputation\n*   Breaches of legal, regulatory or statutory requirements\n*   Breaches of contracts or service levels\n*   Adverse impact on interested parties\n*   Negative impact on the environment, pollution\n\nThe organization determines \"how many categories of consequences are used, how they are defined, and what consequences are associated with each category,\" which can vary depending on the organizations internal and external context. Monetary consequence scales are mentioned as an example, often expressed in a logarithmic scale.\n*   **Document:** `Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx`, Section 6.4.3.2 \"Consequence criteria\".\n\n**3. Integration into Risk Value Calculation:**\n\nThe identified risk impact (RI Value) is a critical component in computing the overall \"Risk Value\" (RV). The process indicates that once vulnerabilities, threats, and likelihood (probability) are identified, the risk value is computed.\n*   **Document:** `Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx`, Section 4.5.1 \"Risk Evaluation (Compute the Risk Value)\" states: \"Once the vulnerabilities, threats and likelihood are identified, the risk value (RV) will be computed for each vulnerability / threat pair to the asset under consideration. The following model will be applied for computing the Risk Value: [model not explicitly detailed in the text but implied by the overall framework].\"\n*   **Document:** `Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx`, Table 3, under \"Risk Assessment\" tasks: \"Identify risk impact (consequences) if vulnerability is exploited\", \"Identify risk probability\", and \"Determine risk value\".\n\nIn summary, the organization uses a **custom, scaled approach** to assess impact, which is categorized from \"Very Low\" to \"Very High\" with corresponding numerical ratings from 1 to 5. This impact rating, alongside probability, feeds into a broader calculation to determine the overall risk value."','2026-02-02 03:24:42','2026-02-02 03:26:26',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(2,'62468ac5c4009b167c669016261cfaff','What rating scale is used for Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability (CIA) impact ratings? What are the levels and definitions for each?','"The rating scale used for Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability (CIA) impact ratings is a **categorical scale** with four levels: **Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, and Extreme.**\n\nThe levels and their definitions for each of Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability impact are as follows:\n\n**Document: Asset Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx**\n**Section: Asset Valuation**\n\"As a preliminary step, the Business Impact on the organization due to the compromise of Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability (C, I, A) of the asset is captured individually and rated across four categories (Insignificant, Moderate, Serious and Extreme).\"\n\nThe guidelines for determining the business impact ratings are as shown below:\n\n\nTABLE 3\n\nDimensions: 5 rows  4 columns\n\nBusiness Impact Rating | Loss of Confidentiality                                                                                                                                                                                    | Loss of Integrity                                                                                                                     | Loss of Availability                                                                                                                                                               \n\nInsignificant          | Disclosure within or outside the organization will not harm the interest of the organization but maybe considered inappropriate.                                                                           | Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have a low adverse effect on business operations.                   | Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have a low adverse effect on business operations.                  \nModerate               | Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization may harm the interest of the organization.                                                                                                      | Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have a moderate adverse effect on business operations.              | Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have a moderate adverse effect on business operations.             \nSerious                | Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization would cause significant harm to the interest of the organization.                                                                               | Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have a serious adverse effect on business operations.               | Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have a serious adverse effect on business operations.              \nExtreme                | Unauthorized disclosure within or outside the organization would cause serious damage to the interests of the organization. Disclosure within the organization will be strictly on a need-to-know basis. | Unauthorized modification or damage of information is expected to have severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations. | Impact of disruption of access or unavailability of information or information asset or services is expected to have severe and long ranging adverse effect on business operations.\n"','2026-02-02 03:26:37','2026-02-02 03:26:37',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(3,'98152a26e253087d1175dd0b2ddacdc8','How is Asset Business Value calculated or determined from CIA impact ratings? Is there a matrix, chart, or formula? What are the Asset Business Value levels?','"The Asset Business Value is calculated or determined from CIA (Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability) impact ratings using a multi-step process involving preliminary impact ratings and a specific \"Asset Value Chart\" (matrix).\n\nHere''s a detailed breakdown:\n\n**1. How Asset Business Value is Calculated or Determined from CIA Impact Ratings:**\n\nAs a preliminary step, the **Business Impact** on the organization due to the compromise of Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability (C, I, A) of the asset is captured individually. This impact can be regulatory, financial, customer service impact, health and safety impact, operational impact, or reputational impact. Each of these individual impacts (for C, I, and A) is rated across four categories:\n\n*   **Insignificant**\n*   **Moderate**\n*   **Serious**\n*   **Extreme**\n\nThe guidelines for determining these individual business impact ratings are provided below:\n\n**Business Impact Rating Definitions for C, I, A:**\nThe Asset Management Guidelines state: \"Once the Business Impact Ratings for the compromise of the C, I and A of the asset are determined then the overall Asset Business Value is determined by below Asset Value Chart as shown below\".\n\nThis \"Asset Value Chart\" functions as a matrix.\n\n**Matrix for Determining Asset Business Value (Asset Value Chart):**\n\n| Integrity     | Confidentiality | Insignificant | Moderate | Serious | Extreme |\n|---------------||||||\n|               | **Availability**  | Insignificant | Moderate | Serious | Extreme |\n| Insignificant |                 | Very low      | Very low | Medium  | High    |\n| Moderate      |                 | Very low      | Low      | Medium  | High    |\n| Serious       |                 | Medium        | Medium   | High    | High    |\n| Extreme       |                 | High          | High     | High    | Very High |\n\n*Source: Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx, Sheet: Asset Inventorization Guideline; Asset Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 (for Business Impact Rating Definitions) and implicit reference to the chart*\n\n**Explanation of the Matrix:**\n\n1.  First, the business impact on the organization due to the loss of Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability for the asset is rated individually using the categories: Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, and Extreme.\n2.  To find the \"Asset Business Value\" using the matrix:\n    *   Locate the **Integrity** rating in the \"Integrity\" row header (leftmost column).\n    *   Locate the **Confidentiality** rating in the \"Confidentiality\" row header.\n    *   Locate the **Availability** rating in the \"Availability\" column header (top row, under Confidentiality).\n    *   The intersection of these three ratings in the chart provides the **Asset Business Value**.\n\n**Example (from the document):**\n\"For example: If the Ratings for a particular asset have been determined as: Confidentiality-Moderate, Availability-Moderate, Integrity-Serious, then the Asset Business Value is \"High\".\"\n*(Note: The example in the document''s Excel file uses \"Low\" instead of \"Moderate\" for Confidentiality and Availability, but \"Low\" is not an allowed input rating. The provided matrix only uses Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, Extreme. Therefore, the example has been adjusted here to match the matrix''s input categories and its corresponding output.)*\n\n**Formula for Automated Derivation:**\n\nIn the `Asset Inventory` sheet of `Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx`, the Asset Business Value is automatically derived using a `VLOOKUP` formula. The formula concatenates the individual C, I, and A impact ratings to form a lookup key and then finds the corresponding Asset Business Value from a predefined lookup table (matrix).\n\nFor example, in `Asset Inventory` sheet, Cell `I7` (Asset business value) contains the formula:\n`=VLOOKUP(F7&G7&H7, $Y$139:$Z$202, 2, 0)`\n\n*   `F7` represents the \"Business Impact - due to loss of Confidentiality\".\n*   `G7` represents the \"Business Impact - due to loss of Integrity\".\n*   `H7` represents the \"Business Impact - due to loss of Availability\".\n*   `$Y$139:$Z$202` is the lookup table (matrix) where column `Y` contains the concatenated CIA impact ratings (e.g., \"InsignificantSeriousSerious\") and column `Z` contains the corresponding \"Asset Business Value\".\n*   `2` indicates that the second column of the lookup range (`$Z$139:$Z$202`) should be returned.\n*   `0` (or FALSE) specifies an exact match.\n\nThis confirms that a matrix (lookup table) is used, and a formula (`VLOOKUP`) automates this lookup in the Excel template.\n\n**2. Asset Business Value Levels:**\n\nThe determined Asset Business Value falls into one of the following five levels:\n\n*   **Very Low**\n*   **Low**\n*   **Medium**\n*   **High**\n*   **Very High**\n\nThese Asset Business Value levels are then used to classify assets for criticality.\n\n**Asset Business Value and Corresponding Criticality Classification:**\n\n\nAsset Business Value | Asset Criticality Classification | Description                                                        \n\nVery Low             | Insignificant                    | Very low impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised \nLow                  | Low Critical                     | Low impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised      \nMedium               | Medium Critical                  | Medium impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised   \nHigh                 | High Critical                    | High impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised     \nVery high            | Very high Critical               | Very high impact on business if C,I and A of asset gets compromised\n\n*Source: Asset Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 4; Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx, Sheet: Asset Inventorization Guideline*"','2026-02-02 03:27:20','2026-02-02 03:27:20',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(4,'e09bdf7487029c7de30463220c5a015e','risk quantification methodology','"The organization''s risk quantification methodology, as detailed in the provided knowledge base, involves evaluating Risk Impact, Risk Probability, deriving a Risk Value, determining a Risk Evaluation Rating, calculating a Control Rating, and finally, a Residual Risk Value.\n\nHere is a breakdown of the methodology:\n\n### 1. Risk Identification and Impact/Probability Assessment\n\nThe process starts with identifying assets, threats, vulnerabilities, and then the associated risk impact and probability.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n    *   **Table 3, SN: Risk Assessment**\n        *   \"Identify risk impact (consequences) if vulnerability is exploited\"\n        *   \"Identify risk probability\"\n        *   \"Determine risk value\"\n        *   \"Identify risk evaluation rating based on the risk value\"\n\n### 2. Risk Impact Evaluation (Compute the ''RI Value'')\n\nImpact is quantified as a numerical quantity reflecting damage.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n    *   **Section 4.4.5 Identify the Risk Impact**: \"Impact shall be quantified as a numerical quantity to reflect damage if a given threat successfully exploits an associated vulnerability. Risk impact value rates the seriousness of a given risk on a relative scale, independent of its probability.\"\n    *   **Section 4.5.2 Risk Impact Evaluation (Compute the ''RI Value'')**: \"For the Risk Assessment the following scale shall be used to estimate the Risk Impact.\"\n    *   **Table 4: Risk Impact Scale**\n        ```\n        \n        TABLE 4\n        \n        Dimensions: 6 rows  3 columns\n\n        Impact Category | Impact Definition                                                | Impact Rating\n        \n        Very Low        | Risk has negligible impact on business and operations            | 1            \n        Low             | Risk does not have significant impact on business and operations | 2            \n        Medium          | Risk has minimum impact on business and operations               | 3            \n        High            | Risk has serious impact on business and operations               | 4            \n        Very High       | Risk has catastrophic impact on business and operations          | 5            \n        \n        ```\n\n### 3. Risk Probability Evaluation (Compute the ''RP Value'')\n\nProbability is the likelihood of a threat exploiting a vulnerability.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n    *   **Section 4.4.6 Identify Risk Probability**: \"Probability is the likelihood of occurrence of a threat exploiting an identified vulnerability on an asset class. Probability of the threat or failure should be captured after considering the vulnerabilities identified\"\n    *   **Section 4.5.3 Risk Probability Evaluation (Compute the ''RP Value'')**: \"For the purposes of Risk Assessment the following scale shall be used to quantify probability.\"\n    *   **Table 5: Risk Probability Scale**\n        ```\n        \n        TABLE 5\n        \n        Dimensions: 6 rows  3 columns\n\n        Probability Category | Probability Definition                       | Probability Rating\n        \n        Very Low             | Greater than one year                        | 1                 \n        Low                  | Once every year                              | 2                 \n        Medium               | Moderate / Medium: once every 4-6 months     | 3                 \n        High                 | Major / High: once every 1-3 months          | 4                 \n        Very High            | Severe / Very high: more than once per month | 5                 \n        \n        ```\n\n### 4. Deriving the Risk Value (RV) and Risk Evaluation Rating\n\nAfter identifying impact and probability, the Risk Value (RV) is computed.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n    *   **Section 4.4.7 Derive the risk value**: \"Derive the risk value as per 4.5.1 Risk Evaluation\"\n    *   **Section 4.5.1 Risk Evaluation (Compute the ''Risk Value'')**: \"Once the vulnerabilities, threats and likelihood are identified, the risk value (RV) will be computed for each vulnerability / threat pair to the asset under consideration. The following model will be applied for computing the Risk Value:\"\n        *   **Note**: The explicit formula for computing the Risk Value (RV) is not provided in the text content, although the context implies it''s derived from Risk Impact (RI) and Risk Probability (RP).\n    *   **Section 4.5.4 Risk Evaluation Rating**: \"Risk evaluation rating is bucketing of risk value as per table below:\"\n    *   **Table 6: Risk Evaluation Rating**\n        ```\n        \n        TABLE 6\n        \n        Dimensions: 6 rows  3 columns\n\n        Risk Rating | Risk value score | Risk Rating\n        \n        1           | 0 to 5           |            \n        2           | 6 to 10          |            \n        3           | 11 to 15         |            \n        4           | 16 to 20         |            \n        5           | 21 to 25         |            \n        \n        ```\n\n### 5. Control Rating\n\nControls (preventive, detective, corrective) are identified and rated to reduce risk.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n    *   **Section 4.6.1 Treat**: \"Controls shall be identified basis preventive, detective and corrective controls which are already in place in organizations environment, to minimize the impact of the respective risks due to the underlying vulnerabilities and threats. The controls are rated on a scale of 1 to 5, basis the following rating definitions defined below.\"\n    *   **Control Rating Formula**: \"The control rating is calculated based on the value of Preventive, Detective, and Corrective control rating. Weightage of preventive control is taken as 1, weightage of detective control is taken as 0.75 and weightage of Corrective controls is taken as 0.5; in order to proactively reduce the probability and impact of the threat to materialize.\"\n        `Control Rating = FLOOR (AVERAGE (Preventive Control Rating *1, Detective Control Rating *0.75, Corrective Control Rating*0.5))`\n    *   **Table 8: Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating Definition**\n        ```\n        \n        TABLE 8\n        \n        Dimensions: 6 rows  2 columns\n\n        Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating | Definition                                                                \n        \n        1                                              | Non-existent or has major deficiencies and do not operate as intended.    \n        2                                              | Limited, high level of risk remains, significant deficiencies.            \n        3                                              | Controls in place with few deficiencies in terms of medium risk issues.   \n        4                                              | Designed and operating, with few deficiencies in terms of low risk issues.\n        5                                              | Designed and operating, with no deficiencies.                             \n        \n        ```\n\n### 6. Residual Risk Value\n\nThe residual risk is determined after considering the effectiveness of controls.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n    *   **Section 4.6.1 Treat**: \"The difference between risk evaluation rating and control rating shall be considered to determine residual risk value basis which Management Decision shall be triggered\"\n    *   **Residual Risk Formula**: `Calculation of Residual Risk value = Risk Evaluation Rating  Control Rating`\n    *   \"Residual Risk value shall be either 1, 2, 3, 4 or 5.\"\n\nThis comprehensive approach allows the organization to numerically quantify risks, evaluate their significance, and measure the effectiveness of implemented controls to arrive at a residual risk level."','2026-02-02 03:29:27','2026-02-02 03:34:55',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(6,'e80e58a26af00cdb471bf590b6a0e535','risk calculation formula','"Based on the provided documents, the risk calculation formulas are derived from the \"Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\".\n\nThe organization uses the following formulas and associated scales for risk calculation:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Risk Value (RV) / Initial Risk Evaluation Rating\n\nWhile not explicitly stated as a direct mathematical formula in text, the \"Risk Management Guidelines\" document implies a multiplicative calculation for Risk Value (RV) based on the provided scales for Risk Impact (RI) and Risk Probability (RP), and the resulting Risk Value scores.\n\n**Implicit Formula:**\n`Risk Value = Risk Impact Rating  Risk Probability Rating`\n\n**Supporting Details:**\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n*   **Section:** 4.5.1 Risk Evaluation (Compute the Risk Value)\n    *   \"Once the vulnerabilities, threats and likelihood are identified, the risk value (RV) will be computed for each vulnerability / threat pair to the asset under consideration. The following model will be applied for computing the Risk Value:\"\n    *   This section introduces the computation of Risk Value (RV).\n*   **Section:** 4.5.2 Risk Impact Evaluation (Compute the RI Value)\n    *   \"For the Risk Assessment the following scale shall be used to estimate the Risk Impact.\"\n    *   Refers to **TABLE 4** (reproduced below).\n*   **Section:** 4.5.3 Risk Probability Evaluation (Compute the RP Value)\n    *   \"For the purposes of Risk Assessment the following scale shall be used to quantify probability.\"\n    *   Refers to **TABLE 5** (reproduced below).\n*   **Section:** 4.5.4 Risk Evaluation Rating\n    *   \"Risk evaluation rating is bucketing of risk value as per table below:\"\n    *   Refers to **TABLE 6** (reproduced below), which shows \"Risk value score\" ranging from 0 to 25. A multiplication of the 1-5 scales from Table 4 and Table 5 would yield a range of 1x1=1 to 5x5=25, perfectly aligning with the \"Risk value score\".\n\n**Scales used for Risk Impact and Risk Probability:**\n\n**TABLE 4: Risk Impact Evaluation (RI Value)**\n\nDimensions: 6 rows  3 columns\n\nImpact Category | Impact Definition                                                | Impact Rating\n\nVery Low        | Risk has negligible impact on business and operations            | 1            \nLow             | Risk does not have significant impact on business and operations | 2            \nMedium          | Risk has minimum impact on business and operations               | 3            \nHigh            | Risk has serious impact on business and operations               | 4            \nVery High       | Risk has catastrophic impact on business and operations          | 5            \n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, TABLE 4\n\n**TABLE 5: Risk Probability Evaluation (RP Value)**\n\nDimensions: 6 rows  3 columns\n\nProbability Category | Probability Definition                       | Probability Rating\n\nVery Low             | Greater than one year                        | 1                 \nLow                  | Once every year                              | 2                 \nMedium               | Moderate / Medium: once every 4-6 months     | 3                 \nHigh                 | Major / High: once every 1-3 months          | 4                 \nVery High            | Severe / Very high: more than once per month | 5                 \n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, TABLE 5\n\n**Mapping from Risk Value Score to Risk Rating:**\n\n**TABLE 6: Risk Evaluation Rating**\n\nDimensions: 6 rows  3 columns\n\nRisk Rating | Risk value score | Risk Rating\n\n1           | 0 to 5           |            \n2           | 6 to 10          |            \n3           | 11 to 15         |            \n4           | 16 to 20         |            \n5           | 21 to 25         |            \n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, TABLE 6\n\n---\n\n### 2. Control Rating\n\nThe control rating is calculated using a weighted average of Preventive, Detective, and Corrective control ratings.\n\n**Explicit Formula:**\n`Control Rating = FLOOR (AVERAGE (Preventive Control Rating *1, Detective Control Rating *0.75, Corrective Control Rating*0.5))`\n\n**Supporting Details:**\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n*   **Section:** 4.6.1 Treat\n    *   \"The control rating is calculated based on the value of Preventive, Detective, and Corrective control rating. Weightage of preventive control is taken as 1, weightage of detective control is taken as 0.75 and weightage of Corrective controls is taken as 0.5; in order to proactively reduce the probability and impact of the threat to materialize.\"\n*   **Scales used for Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating:**\n\n**TABLE 8: Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating**\n\nDimensions: 6 rows  2 columns\n\nPreventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating | Definition                                                                \n\n1                                              | Non-existent or has major deficiencies and do not operate as intended.    \n2                                              | Limited, high level of risk remains, significant deficiencies.            \n3                                              | Controls in place with few deficiencies in terms of medium risk issues.   \n4                                              | Designed and operating, with few deficiencies in terms of low risk issues.\n5                                              | Designed and operating, with no deficiencies.                             \n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, TABLE 8\n\n---\n\n### 3. Residual Risk Value\n\nThe residual risk value is determined by subtracting the Control Rating from the initial Risk Evaluation Rating.\n\n**Explicit Formula:**\n`Residual Risk value = Risk Evaluation Rating  Control Rating`\n\n**Supporting Details:**\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx\n*   **Section:** 4.6.1 Treat\n    *   \"The difference between risk evaluation rating and control rating shall be considered to determine residual risk value basis which Management Decision shall be triggered\"\n    *   \"Residual Risk value shall be either 1, 2, 3, 4 or 5.\"\n\n---\n\n### Additional Context on Risk Level Determination (ISO/IEC 27005:2022)\n\nThe ISO/IEC 27005-2022 document, while providing general guidance, does not specify a concrete mathematical formula but reiterates the principle that risk levels are a combination of consequences and likelihood.\n\n*   **Document:** ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf\n*   **Section:** 3.1.15 level of risk\n    *   \"significance of a risk (3.1.3 ), expressed in terms of the combination of consequences (3.1.14 ) and their likelihood (3.1.13 )\"\n*   **Section:** 7.3.4 Determining the levels of risk\n    *   \"The levels of risk are determined by combining the assessed consequences (7.3.2) and likelihoods (7.3.3) of the identified risks, using the established risk criteria (6.4).\"\n    *   This confirms that the organization''s own defined criteria (as found in the \"Risk Management Guidelines\") would contain the specific method for combining these elements."','2026-02-02 03:35:21','2026-02-02 03:35:21',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(8,'c05dd234e3a1581d9bb69b756424b7d1','control framework','"While the term \"control framework\" is not explicitly defined as a standalone entity in the provided documents, the concept is comprehensively addressed through the descriptions of various **Risk Management Frameworks** (RMFs) that integrate and manage controls as a core component of risk management.\n\nHere''s a detailed breakdown based on the provided documents:\n\n### Definition of a \"Control\"\n\nThe foundational element of any control framework is a \"control.\"\n\n*   **Definition:** A control is a \"measure that maintains and/or modifies risk.\" Controls include, but are not limited to, any process, policy, device, practice, or other conditions and/or actions which maintain and/or modify risk. Controls may not always exert the intended or assumed modifying effect.\n    *   *(Source: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 3.8, page 2; ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.1.16, page 4)*\n\n### NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF)\n\nThe NIST RMF (Special Publication 800-37, Revision 2) serves as a robust control framework for managing security and privacy risks, particularly for information systems and organizations.\n\n*   **Purpose:** The RMF provides a disciplined, structured, and flexible process for managing security and privacy risk. Its objective is to increase the effectiveness, efficiency, and cost-effectiveness of security and privacy risk management processes.\n    *   *(Source: NIST. Risk Management Framework 800-37r2.pdf, Abstract, page ii; Executive Summary, page vi)*\n*   **Key Activities involving Controls:** The RMF specifically includes:\n    *   **Control Selection:** Identifying appropriate security and privacy controls.\n    *   **Control Implementation:** Putting selected controls into practice.\n    *   **Control Assessment:** Evaluating the effectiveness of implemented controls.\n    *   **Continuous Monitoring:** Ongoing oversight of controls.\n    *   **Authorization:** Granting authorization based on accepted security and privacy risks, informed by control implementation and assessment.\n    *   **Preparation:** Activities to prepare organizations for RMF execution, including organization-wide identification of common controls and development of organizationally-tailored control baselines.\n    *   *(Source: NIST. Risk Management Framework 800-37r2.pdf, Abstract, page ii; Executive Summary, page vii)*\n*   **Control Types & Approaches:**\n    *   **Common Controls:** Maximize the use of common controls at the organizational level to promote standardized, consistent, and cost-effective security and privacy capability inheritance.\n    *   **Organizationally-Tailored Control Baselines:** Employ these to increase the speed of security and privacy plan development and consistency.\n    *   **Organization-Defined Controls:** Based on security and privacy requirements from a systems security engineering process.\n    *   **Control Catalog:** Supports the use of a consolidated control catalog (e.g., NIST Special Publication 800-53, Revision 5).\n    *   *(Source: NIST. Risk Management Framework 800-37r2.pdf, Executive Summary, page vii)*\n*   **Nature:** The RMF is technology-neutral, designed to be applied to any type of information system without modification, and supports iterative application throughout the system development life cycle, including Agile and DevOps approaches. It encourages automation for increased speed and efficiency in control assessment and monitoring.\n    *   *(Source: NIST. Risk Management Framework 800-37r2.pdf, \"THE RMF IS TECHNOLOGY NEUTRAL,\" page xi; \"USE OF AUTOMATION IN THE EXECUTION OF THE RMF,\" page xii)*\n*   **Applicability:** Mandatory for federal government use, and encouraged for nonfederal organizations, including those using the NIST Cybersecurity Framework, for control implementation, assessment, and monitoring.\n    *   *(Source: NIST. Risk Management Framework 800-37r2.pdf, \"SCOPE AND APPLICABILITY,\" page xiii)*\n\n### Risk Management Framework (from Risk Management Guidelines)\n\nThis document outlines a risk management framework focused on protecting information system assets by systematically managing risks through controls.\n\n*   **Purpose:** Ensures all Information System assets are adequately protected.\n    *   *(Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, \"Risk Management Framework,\" page 10)*\n*   **Key Activities involving Controls:**\n    *   **Risk Identification and Assessment:** Identifying threats and vulnerabilities.\n    *   **Risk Treatment:** Implementing appropriate controls to reduce risks when the risk evaluation rating is above 2. This aims to bring the risk evaluation rating to an acceptable level (1 or 2).\n    *   **Measurement and Monitoring Risk:** Defining metrics to monitor the effectiveness of risk treatment and maintaining trends for control efficiency.\n    *   **Risk Acceptance:** Decision to accept residual risks, sometimes after controls are implemented or if controls are not feasible.\n    *   *(Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, \"Risk Management Framework,\" page 10; \"Risk Treatment,\" page 15; \"Identify measurement metrics to monitor effectiveness of risk treatment,\" page 18)*\n*   **Control Rating Formula:**\n    Controls are rated on a scale of 1 to 5. The control rating is calculated to determine residual risk.\n    `Control Rating = FLOOR (AVERAGE (Preventive Control Rating *1, Detective Control Rating *0.75, Corrective Control Rating*0.5))`\n    `Calculation of Residual Risk value = Risk Evaluation Rating  Control Rating`\n    *   *(Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, \"Treat,\" page 15)*\n\n*   **Control Rating Definitions:**\n\n    | Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating | Definition                                                                |\n    | :--------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n    | 1                                              | Non-existent or has major deficiencies and do not operate as intended.    |\n    | 2                                              | Limited, high level of risk remains, significant deficiencies.            |\n    | 3                                              | Controls in place with few deficiencies in terms of medium risk issues.   |\n    | 4                                              | Designed and operating, with few deficiencies in terms of low risk issues. |\n    | 5                                              | Designed and operating, with no deficiencies.                             |\n    *   *(Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 8, page 17)*\n\n*   **Examples of Controls and Monitoring Metrics:**\n    This framework specifies controls across various domains with associated measurement and trend metrics (e.g., Unsuccessful login attempts for Authentication and Authorization, Percentage of laptops not encrypted for Encryption, List of devices not hardened for Hardening).\n    *   *(Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 10, page 18)*\n\n### ISO 31000:2018 Risk Management Framework\n\nISO 31000 provides guidelines for managing risk, establishing a framework that enables the effective management of risks, which inherently includes the application of controls.\n\n*   **Purpose:** \"The purpose of the risk management framework is to assist the organization in integrating risk management into significant activities and functions. The effectiveness of risk management will depend on its integration into the governance of the organization, including decision-making.\"\n    *   *(Source: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 5.1, page 4)*\n*   **Framework Components:**\n    The framework development encompasses:\n    *   **Leadership and commitment:** Top management ensuring risk management is integrated and resources are allocated.\n    *   **Integration:** Risk management as an integral part of all organizational activities.\n    *   **Design:** Understanding context, articulating commitment, assigning roles (including identifying risk owners), allocating resources (people, skills, processes, methods, tools), and establishing communication and consultation.\n    *   **Implementation:** Developing plans, modifying decision-making processes, ensuring arrangements are understood and practiced.\n    *   **Evaluation:** Periodically measuring framework performance.\n    *   **Improvement:** Continually monitoring, adapting, and improving the framework.\n    *   *(Source: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 5, Figure 3, page 4; Sections 5.2-5.7, pages 5-8)*\n*   **Role of Controls in the Process:** The risk management process (which operates within the framework) involves assessing and treating risk. \"Risk treatment\" involves selecting and implementing options for addressing risk, which explicitly includes \"measures that maintain and/or modify risk\" (controls).\n    *   *(Source: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 3.8, page 2; Section 6.5, page 13)*\n\n### ISO/IEC 27005:2022 and ISO 27001 Controls\n\nISO/IEC 27005 provides guidance for managing information security risks within the context of an Information Security Management System (ISMS) as defined by ISO/IEC 27001, which is a key control framework for information security.\n\n*   **Purpose:** To assist organizations in fulfilling ISO/IEC 27001 requirements for addressing information security risks and performing risk assessment and treatment.\n    *   *(Source: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Introduction, page vi; Section 1, page 1)*\n*   **Control Integration:** The document details the process for \"Determining all controls that are necessary to implement the information security risk treatment options.\" This involves:\n    *   Identifying controls based on risk treatment options.\n    *   Considering existing controls.\n    *   Referencing control sets like **ISO/IEC 27001:2022, Annex A**, as a source for information security controls.\n    *   Selecting, customizing, and justifying controls, including deciding if the ISO/IEC 27001 Annex A controls are fully applicable, not applicable, or if additional controls are needed.\n    *   *(Source: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.3, page 24; Section 8.4, page 27)*\n*   **Statement of Applicability (SoA):** The output of this control selection and justification process is a Statement of Applicability.\n    *   *(Source: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.5, page 27)*\n\n### Examples of Controls (from ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx)\n\nThis document lists specific controls that would be part of an organization''s control framework, categorized by ISO 27001 themes and ITGC domains.\n\n*   **ISO 27001 Controls Categorization:**\n    *   **Organizational Controls (37 Controls):** Focus on governance, policies, roles, risk, and supplier management.\n        *   Example: A.5.1. Policies for information security, A.5.2. Information security roles and responsibilities, A.5.7 Threat intelligence, A.5.23 Information security for use of cloud services, A.5.34 Privacy and protection of PII.\n    *   **People Controls (8 Controls):** Focus on human resource security, awareness, and disciplinary measures.\n        *   Example: A.6.1 Screening, A.6.3 Information security awareness, education, and training, A.6.4 Disciplinary process, A.6.7 Remote working.\n    *   **Physical Controls (14 Controls):** Focus on physical and environmental security.\n        *   Example: A.7.1 Physical security perimeters, A.7.2 Physical entry controls, A.7.5 Protection against physical and environmental threats, A.7.12 Cabling security, A.7.14 Secure disposal or re-use of equipment.\n    *   **Technological Controls (34 Controls):** Cover system security, operations, networks, and monitoring.\n        *   Example: A.8.2 Privileged access rights, A.8.7 Protection against malware, A.8.9 Configuration management, A.8.12 Data leakage prevention, A.8.20 Networks security, A.8.24 Secure development lifecycle, A.8.31 Change management.\n    *   *(Source: ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx, Sheet: ISO 27001 Conrols)*\n\n*   **Main ITGC Domains and Example Controls:**\n    *   **1. Access to Programs and Data (Logical Access Controls):** User access provisioning and de-provisioning, Periodic user access review, Privileged access management, Password and authentication policies, Segregation of duties, Remote access controls.\n    *   **2. Program Change Management:** Change request initiation and approval, Change testing and documentation, Segregation of development and production, Emergency change management, Version control, Change deployment authorization.\n    *   **3. Program Development (SDLC Controls):** Project approval and feasibility review, Requirements documentation, Design and coding standards, User acceptance testing (UAT), Post-implementation review.\n    *   **4. Computer Operations (IT Operations):** Job scheduling and monitoring, Backup and recovery, Incident and problem management, Batch job failure handling, Data center physical security, Capacity and performance monitoring.\n    *   **5. System / Infrastructure Security (Technical Controls):** Patch management, Antivirus / endpoint protection, Firewall and network controls, Vulnerability assessments, System hardening, Logging and monitoring.\n    *   **6. IT Governance / Policy Management:** IT policies and procedures, Risk assessment, Roles and responsibilities, Training and awareness, IT steering committee reviews.\n    *   *(Source: ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx, Sheet: ITGC Controls)*\n\nIn summary, a control framework, as depicted across these documents, is a structured system (like the NIST RMF or an ISMS based on ISO 27001/27005) that encompasses policies, processes, and practices for identifying, selecting, implementing, assessing, monitoring, and improving controls to manage various types of risks (especially security and privacy risks) to an acceptable level, aligned with organizational objectives and regulatory requirements."','2026-02-02 03:37:07','2026-02-02 03:37:07',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(9,'e5a75ea1bd8bb18a30c16f12400c10cf','Risk Treatment Decision options TREAT ACCEPT TRANSFER TERMINATE','"Error searching knowledge base: 429 You exceeded your current quota, please check your plan and billing details. For more information on this error, head to: https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/rate-limits. To monitor your current usage, head to: https://ai.dev/rate-limit. \n* Quota exceeded for metric: generativelanguage.googleapis.com/generate_content_free_tier_requests, limit: 20, model: gemini-2.5-flash\nPlease retry in 29.755367496s. [links {\n  description: \"Learn more about Gemini API quotas\"\n  url: \"https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/rate-limits\"\n}\n, violations {\n  quota_metric: \"generativelanguage.googleapis.com/generate_content_free_tier_requests\"\n  quota_id: \"GenerateRequestsPerDayPerProjectPerModel-FreeTier\"\n  quota_dimensions {\n    key: \"model\"\n    value: \"gemini-2.5-flash\"\n  }\n  quota_dimensions {\n    key: \"location\"\n    value: \"global\"\n  }\n  quota_value: 20\n}\n, retry_delay {\n  seconds: 29\n}\n]"','2026-02-02 03:40:26','2026-02-02 05:46:16',22);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(10,'34ba0439953935ed7773c0ce666433c0','TREAT risk treatment option definition recommendation consequences cost timeline approval monitoring','"The \"TREAT\" risk treatment option involves implementing controls to reduce identified risks to an acceptable level.\n\nHere is a detailed breakdown based on the provided documents:\n\n### Definition\nThe \"Treat\" risk treatment option is defined as implementing appropriate controls to reduce risks, aiming to bring down the risk evaluation rating to an acceptable level (1 or 2). This involves modifying the risk by changing its likelihood or consequences through preventive, detective, and corrective controls.\n*   **Source:**\n    *   \"All risks with risk evaluation rating above 2 shall be treated by implementing appropriate controls. These controls will attempt to reduce the risks and bring down the risk evaluation rating to the acceptable level (1 or 2).\"\n    *   \"Controls shall be identified basis preventive, detective and corrective controls which are already in place in organizations environment, to minimize the impact of the respective risks due to the underlying vulnerabilities and threats.\"\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1)\n    *   Risk treatment can involve \"changing the likelihood\" or \"changing the consequences.\"\n    *   (ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.7 Note 1 to entry)\n    *   The task involves identifying appropriate preventive, detective, and corrective controls to reduce the risk.\n    *   (Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 18)\n\n### Recommendation\n*   **When to Treat:** All risks with a risk evaluation rating above 2 shall be treated. Risks with a risk rating range of 3 to 5 are classified as \"Non Acceptable Risk,\" requiring necessary corrective and preventive controls to be implemented.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1 and Table 7)\n*   **Action:** Identify and implement appropriate preventive, detective, and corrective controls to reduce the risk.\n    *   (Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 18)\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1)\n*   **Control Rating:** Controls are rated on a scale of 1 to 5 based on their effectiveness.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1)\n    *   The control rating is calculated with weightages:\n        *   Preventive Control Rating * 1\n        *   Detective Control Rating * 0.75\n        *   Corrective Control Rating * 0.5\n    *   **Formula:** `Control Rating = FLOOR (AVERAGE (Preventive Control Rating *1, Detective Control Rating *0.75, Corrective Control Rating*0.5))`\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1)\n*   **Control Rating Definitions:**\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 8)\n    \n    TABLE 8\n    \n    Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating | Definition\n    \n    1                                              | Non-existent or has major deficiencies and do not operate as intended.\n    2                                              | Limited, high level of risk remains, significant deficiencies.\n    3                                              | Controls in place with few deficiencies in terms of medium risk issues.\n    4                                              | Designed and operating, with few deficiencies in terms of low risk issues.\n    5                                              | Designed and operating, with no deficiencies.\n    \n\n### Consequences\n*   **Objective:** The primary consequence is the reduction of risk evaluation rating to the acceptable level (1 or 2).\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1)\n*   **Residual Risk:** The risk remaining after risk treatment. The difference between the original risk evaluation rating and the control rating determines the residual risk value.\n    *   **Formula:** `Calculation of Residual Risk value = Risk Evaluation Rating  Control Rating`\n    *   The Residual Risk value shall be either 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1)\n    *   After treatment, the expected residual risk level can be Low, Medium, or High.\n    *   (Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Section 4)\n*   **Other consequences tracked:** Risk Reduction Percentage and Risk Trend (Improving/Stable/Worsening).\n    *   (Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Section 6)\n\n### Cost\nThe provided documents do not specify a direct \"cost\" associated with the \"Treat\" risk treatment option itself. However, they indicate that financial feasibility is a consideration when deciding *not* to treat (i.e., accepting) a risk, and a cost-benefit analysis is performed for *transferring* risk. This implies that cost is an underlying factor in risk treatment decisions, but specific cost calculation or reporting for \"Treat\" is not detailed.\n*   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.4 for \"Accept\", Section 4.6.3 for \"Transfer\")\n*   (ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 6.4.2 d) mentions cost/benefit balance for risk acceptance criteria)\n\n### Timeline\n*   The Risk Treatment Plan shall include **proposed deadlines** to start and complete the risk treatment.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.7)\n    *   The plan should identify **estimated start and completion dates** for the implementation of selected controls.\n    *   (ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.6.1)\n*   For each specific treatment action, a **deadline** is to be provided.\n    *   (Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Section 3)\n*   An **Expected Completion Date** is tracked in the Risk Followup Form.\n    *   (Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Section 5)\n\n### Approval\n*   **Risk Treatment Plan Development:** The Asset Class Owner develops the Risk Treatment Plan.\n*   **Approval Authority:** The Risk Treatment Plan must be **approved by the Risk Owner**.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.7)\n    *   The Asset Class Owner obtains approval for the plan, and the Risk Owner reviews and approves it.\n    *   (Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 34 & 36)\n*   Risk Owners should also approve that the residual information security risks are acceptable.\n    *   (ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.6.2)\n\n### Monitoring\n*   **Effectiveness Metrics:** Measurement metrics shall be defined to ensure controls are effectively implemented and managed. A metrics with trend shall be maintained to measure control efficiency.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.5)\n*   **Monitoring Activities:**\n    *   Measure and monitor the effectiveness of the adopted risk treatment plan.\n    *   Monitor the risk and perform risk assessment periodically.\n    *   (Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 39-40)\n    *   Monitoring of information security risks and controls should be planned, including identification of responsibilities and frequency of review.\n    *   Monitoring includes collecting, processing, and analyzing information like recorded experience, test/audit results, observations, and feedback.\n    *   Results of monitoring and review should be recorded and reported to relevant interested parties.\n    *   (ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 10.5.1)\n*   **Periodic Review:** The risk management process, including risk assessment and treatment plan, should be reviewed once a year, or whenever major changes occur in assets, operations, or the environment. This verifies the effectiveness of new/additional controls.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.10)\n*   **Follow-up Tracking (Treat - Mitigate the Risk):**\n    *   The \"Risk Followup Form\" includes specific questions for monitoring treated risks:\n        *   Have the planned mitigation actions been implemented?\n        *   Are the controls operating effectively?\n        *   Has the likelihood or impact reduced after treatment?\n        *   Is additional treatment required?\n        *   Evidence available for implemented controls (Yes/No, attach reference).\n        *   Current Control Rating\n        *   Current Residual Risk\n        *   Risk Reduction Percentage\n        *   Risk Trend (Improving / Stable / Worsening)\n        *   Last Reassessment Date\n    *   (Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Section 4 and 6)\n*   **Examples of Controls and Measurements for Monitoring Effectiveness:**\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 10)\n    \n    TABLE 10 (Partial, examples for monitoring controls related to treatment)\n     to 14:00 (Risk and Compliance)\n*   **Approval Authority:** The Risk Committee / CRO / Business Head for management approval. For critical risks, Board approval is needed.\n    *   (Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines)\n*   **Risk Owner Approval:** The Risk Owner approves the risks accepted by the Risk Owner which are not falling under risk acceptance criteria.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 2)\n    *   The Risk Owner also reviews and approves the Risk Treatment Plan.\n    *   (Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 36)\n*   **Risk Approver:** Approves the risks accepted by the Risk Owner which are not falling under risk acceptance criteria.\n    *   (Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN 2)"','2026-02-02 05:42:11','2026-02-02 05:46:25',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(11,'88307e071a95c11cd6d3106aebd27c75','TRANSFER risk treatment option definition recommendation consequences cost timeline approval monitoring','"Based on the provided documents, here is the detailed information regarding the TRANSFER risk treatment option:\n\n### 1. Definition\n\nRisk transfer means:\n*   \"shifting financial or operational impact to a third party, while ownership may still partially remain. Important: Risk is never fully transferred, accountability always remains with the organization.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines, Cell A2-A3)\n*   \"Sharing with another party the burden of loss or benefit of gain, for a risk.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 3. Definitions, Table 2, row ''Risk Transfer'')\n*   It is a form of risk treatment that involves \"sharing the risk with another party or parties (including contracts and risk financing).\"\n    *   (Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.7 Note 1)\n*   \"Risk transfer is a form of risk sharing.\" Risk sharing involves \"the agreed distribution of risk with other parties.\"\n    *   (Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.9 Note 4, and Section 3.2.9)\n\n### 2. Recommendation\n\nRisk transfer is recommended under the following conditions and using specified methods:\n\n*   **When to Transfer**: \"Certain risks with risk evaluation rating / final risk value (residual risk) above 2 may be transferred to other parties such as insurers, suppliers or contractors through annual maintenance contracts.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.3 Transfer)\n*   **Procedure - Step-by-Step Process**:\n    *   **Risk Identification & Assessment**: Understand risk severity and financial exposure.\n    *   **Transfer Feasibility Analysis**: Assess the cost of insurance vs. potential loss, vendor capability and maturity, and legal and regulatory acceptance.\n    *   **Select Transfer Mechanism**: Choose between insurance, vendor contract, SLA/indemnity, or third-party agreement.\n    *   **Due Diligence**: Conduct vendor risk assessment, financial stability checks, and compliance checks (e.g., ISO, SOC).\n    *   **Contractual Implementation**: Ensure risk clauses are embedded and liabilities and exclusions are defined.\n    *   **Residual Risk Assessment**: Identify remaining exposure and apply mitigation if required.\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines, Cells A5-A25)\n*   **Common Risk Transfer Methods**:\n    *   Insurance (cyber, liability, professional indemnity)\n    *   Outsourcing / Managed Services\n    *   Contracts & Indemnity Clauses\n    *   SLAs and Penalty Clauses\n    *   Joint ventures / partnerships\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines, Cells C5-C10)\n*   **Specific for Natural Disasters**: \"To transfer the risk of natural disaster, insurance will be made available to the items as mentioned below to cover unexpected emergency losses. Insurance will provide the coverage for the physical damage to the insured assets against fire, lightning, explosion, riot, and impact by any rail/road vehicle, storm, cyclone, flood, earthquake fire and shock.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.3 Transfer)\n    *   **Assets covered through adequate insurance**: Building, Other plant and machinery, Computer hardware and software, Networking equipment, Furniture, fixtures and fittings.\n    *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.3 Transfer)\n*   **Risk Transfer Template Fields**:\n    The following fields are relevant when recommending and documenting a transfer:\n\n| Field                | Description                      |\n| :------------------- | :------------------------------- |\n| Risk ID              | Unique risk identifier           |\n| Risk Description     | Description of the risk          |\n| Root Cause           | Cause of the risk                |\n| Inherent Risk Rating | High / Critical                  |\n| Transfer Method      | Insurance / Vendor / Contract    |\n| Third Party Name     | Insurer / Vendor                 |\n| Scope of Transfer    | What is covered                  |\n| Contract Reference   | Policy / Agreement ID            |\n| Transfer Start Date  | Effective date                   |\n| Transfer End Date    | Expiry date                      |\n| Residual Risk Rating | Medium / Low                     |\n| Risk Owner           | Internal accountable owner       |\n| Review Frequency     | Quarterly / Annually             |\n\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information, Data Range A1-F16)\n\n### 3. Consequences\n\n*   **Accountability Always Remains**: \"Risk is never fully transferred, accountability always remains with the organization.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines, Cell A3)\n*   **Residual Risk**: After transfer, the \"Residual Risk Rating\" is expected to be \"Medium / Low\". This implies a reduction in the initial risk rating which might have been \"High / Critical.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information, Cells A7, A12)\n*   **Dependence on Arrangements**: The \"extent to which risk is distributed can depend on the reliability and clarity of the sharing arrangements.\"\n    *   (Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.9 Note 3)\n*   **Legal/Regulatory Constraints**: \"Legal or regulatory requirements can limit, prohibit or mandate risk sharing.\"\n    *   (Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.9 Note 1)\n\n### 4. Cost\n\n*   **Cost-Benefit Analysis**: \"Prior to arriving at the decision to transfer the risk, a cost benefit analysis shall be done.\"\n    *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.3 Transfer)\n    *   The Risk Owner is responsible to \"Perform cost benefit analysis and transfer risks\".\n        *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.3.1 Roles and responsibilities, Table 3, SN 1)\n*   **Feasibility Analysis**: Considerations include the \"Cost of insurance vs potential loss\".\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines, Cell A8)\n\n### 5. Timeline\n\n*   **Start and End Dates**: The risk transfer mechanism should have a defined \"Transfer Start Date (Effective date)\" and \"Transfer End Date (Expiry date)\".\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information, Cells A10-A11)\n*   **Review Frequency**: The transferred risk should be subject to a \"Review Frequency\" of \"Quarterly / Annually\".\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information, Cell A14)\n\n### 6. Approval\n\n*   **Risk Owner Responsibility**: The \"Risk Owner\" is responsible for initiating the transfer of non-acceptable risks.\n    *   (Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN: Transfer, Task & Responsibility)\n    *   The Risk Owner is also responsible to \"Review and Approve the Risk Treatment Plan\".\n        *   (Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN: Risk Treatment Plan Approval)\n*   **Risk Treatment Plan Approval**: The \"Risk Treatment Plan shall be developed by the asset class owner and approved by the risk owner.\" This plan would encompass the transfer decision.\n    *   (Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v10.docx, Section 4.7 Risk Treatment Plan)\n\n### 7. Monitoring\n\n*   **Periodic Review**: The \"Review Frequency\" for transferred risks is \"Quarterly / Annually\".\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information, Cell A14)\n*   **Residual Risk Assessment**: After transfer, it is necessary to \"Identify remaining exposure\" and \"Apply mitigation if required\".\n    *   (Document: Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines, Cells A24-A25)\n*   **Monitoring and Review of Risks (General)**:\n    *   \"Measure and Monitor the effectiveness of the risk treatment plan adopted\" by the Risk Owner.\n    *   \"Monitor the risk and perform risk assessment periodically\" by the Asset class Owner.\n    *   \"Review accepted risk periodically\" by the Risk Owner.\n    *   \"Review the risk assessment periodically with the asset class owner\" by the Risk Owner.\n    *   (Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, SN: Monitoring and Review of Risks)\n*   **Accepted Risks**: Any residual risks that are accepted after treatment (including transfer) are \"subject to monitoring and review.\"\n    *   (Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.8 Note 2)"','2026-02-02 05:42:41','2026-02-02 05:46:33',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(12,'2b9aa98f68406d4d9d4cd654074edbd8','TERMINATE risk treatment option definition recommendation consequences cost timeline approval monitoring','"Based on the provided documents, here is a detailed breakdown of the \"TERMINATE\" risk treatment option:\n\n---\n\n### **TERMINATE Risk Treatment Option**\n\n**1. Definition:**\n*   **General:** Risk termination means eliminating the activity that causes the risk, so the risk no longer exists. It is also referred to as \"Risk Avoidance.\"\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines*\n*   **Specific Application:** For risks with a high or critical evaluation rating, the risk shall be eliminated by ceasing the activity on the implementation of the objective that presents the risk, or by removing the risk source.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.2*\n    *   *Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.7 Note 1 to entry*\n\n**2. Recommendation (When to apply):**\n*   **Risk Rating:** Recommended for all risks with a risk evaluation rating / final risk value (residual risk) above 2. This includes \"Non Acceptable Risks,\" which have a Risk Rating Range of 3 to 5.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.2, Table 7*\n*   **Inherent Risk:** Applicable for risks with an Inherent Risk Rating of \"High\" or \"Critical.\"\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines*\n*   **Non-Acceptable Risks:** The task of ''Terminate'' involves avoiding non-acceptable risks.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3*\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information (Field: Termination Justification)*\n\n**3. Consequences:**\n*   **Direct Outcome:** The primary consequence is the elimination of the risk by ceasing the activity or removing the risk source.\n*   **Business Impact:** The \"Risk Termination Form\" includes a field to describe the \"Business Impact\" of the termination.\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information*\n*   **Secondary Risks:** It is crucial to ensure that \"no secondary risks remain\" after the termination. Risk treatment, in general, can also \"create new risks or modify existing risks\" and might not always produce expected outcomes or could lead to unintended consequences.\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines*\n    *   *Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.7 Note 4 to entry*\n    *   *Document: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 6.5.2*\n\n**4. Cost:**\n*   **Feasibility Analysis:** Prior to termination, a \"Feasibility Analysis\" should be conducted, which includes evaluating the \"Cost of continuing vs terminating.\"\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines*\n*   **Decision Making:** The selection of risk treatment options, including termination, involves balancing potential benefits against \"costs, effort or disadvantages of implementation.\"\n    *   *Document: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 6.5.2*\n\n**5. Timeline:**\n*   **Completion Date:** The \"Risk Termination Form\" includes a \"Completion Date\" field.\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information*\n*   **Deadlines:** A Risk Treatment Plan, if developed, shall include \"Proposed deadlines to start the risk treatment and the completion of risk treatment.\" This plan specifies \"when actions are expected to be undertaken and completed.\"\n    *   *Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.7*\n    *   *Document: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 6.5.3*\n\n**6. Approval:**\n*   **Risk Owner:** The Risk Owner is responsible for avoiding non-acceptable risks and for reviewing and approving the Risk Treatment Plan.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3*\n    *   *Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3, Section 4.7*\n*   **Management Approval:** \"Management Approval\" is required for termination, specifically \"Approval from Risk Committee / CRO / Business Head,\" and \"Board approval for critical risks.\"\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines*\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information (Approval Authority)*\n*   **Risk Treatment Plan Approval:** The Asset Class Owner obtains approval for the risk treatment plan, which is then reviewed and approved by the Risk Owner. Risk & Compliance provides guidance and consultation.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3*\n    *   *Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.6.2*\n\n**7. Monitoring:**\n*   **Residual Risk Confirmation:** After termination actions (stopping activity, decommissioning, revoking access), it is necessary to \"Validate risk is eliminated\" and \"Ensure no secondary risks remain.\" The \"Residual Risk\" should be \"None / Low\" and the \"Closure Status\" should be \"Closed.\"\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines*\n    *   *Document: Risk Termination template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information*\n*   **Effectiveness Measurement:** Measurement metrics should be identified and maintained with trends to monitor the effectiveness of risk treatment and control efficiency.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.5*\n    *   *Document: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3*\n*   **Periodic Review:** The risk owner is responsible for monitoring the risk and performing risk assessment periodically. The risk management process and its outcomes should be documented and reported. Monitoring and review should be an integral part of risk treatment implementation to assure effectiveness.\n    *   *Document: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.8*\n    *   *Document: ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.1, 10.5.1*\n    *   *Document: ISO-31000.pdf, Section 6.5.2, 6.6, 6.7*\n\n---"','2026-02-02 05:43:15','2026-02-02 05:46:40',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(13,'71bf4a269192d344b547e971335746b7','Risk owner roles approval workflow','"Based on the provided documents, the Risk Owner''s approval workflow is primarily detailed in two key areas: the approval of the **Risk Treatment Plan** and the **acceptance of risks** (which then may require approval from a Risk Approver for higher-rated risks).\n\nHere''s a detailed breakdown:\n\n### 1. Risk Owner''s Role in Risk Acceptance and Subsequent Approval Workflow\n\nThe Risk Owner is responsible for *accepting* risks, particularly those deemed \"non-acceptable\" (Risk Evaluation Rating > 2) where further treatment is not feasible. These accepted risks then require *approval* from a designated Risk Approver.\n\n**Workflow Steps:**\n\n1.  **Risk Identification & Evaluation (Asset Class Owner''s Responsibility):**\n    *   The Asset Class Owner identifies assets, threats, vulnerabilities, determines risk impact, probability, and calculates the risk value.\n    *   They identify the risk evaluation rating based on the risk value.\n    *   They compare the risk evaluation rating / final risk value (residual risk) with the acceptable risk criteria.\n    *   **Acceptable Risk Evaluation Rating:** 1 to 2. Risks with a rating of 1 or 2 are considered acceptable and are accepted by management.\n    *   **Non-Acceptable Risk Evaluation Rating:** 3 to 5. These have a high impact and require necessary corrective and preventive controls.\n    *   If the risk evaluation rating / final risk value (residual risk) is above the risk acceptance criteria (i.e., 3-5), the Asset Class Owner highlights this risk to the Risk Owner.\n    *   *(Reference: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Accept\" section; Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, sections 4.2, 4.6.4, Table 7)*\n\n2.  **Risk Acceptance (Risk Owner''s Responsibility):**\n    *   For risks with an evaluation rating above 2, if implementing controls is not feasible due to financial, administrative, or technical reasons, the **Risk Owner** decides to *accept* the non-acceptable risk.\n    *   Prior to this decision, the Risk Owner performs a cost-benefit analysis.\n    *   The Risk Owner formally *accepts the risk* using the \"Risk Assessment Template\" and \"Risk Acceptance Form\".\n    *   For risks affecting an engagement, approval from the authorized customer approving authority may also be required before the Risk Owner accepts the risk.\n    *   *(Reference: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Accept\" section; Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Risk Owner\" responsibilities; section 4.6.4 \"Accept\")*\n\n3.  **Risk Approval (Risk Approver''s Responsibility):**\n    *   After the Risk Owner *accepts* the risk (specifically those not falling under the risk acceptance criteria, i.e., >2), the **Risk Approver** is responsible for *approving* these accepted risks.\n    *   The approval is recorded on the \"Risk Assessment Template\" and \"Risk Acceptance Form\".\n    *   *(Reference: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Accept\" section; Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Risk Approver\" responsibilities)*\n\n**Responsible Parties for Risk Acceptance/Approval:**\n\nThe specific individuals or departments acting as Risk Owner and Risk Approver depend on the impact coverage of the risk:\n\n| Impact coverage                                                                | Risk Owner          | Risk Approver                     |\n| :----------------------------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------ | :-------------------------------- |\n| Contractual non compliance                                                     | CIO/ Legal/ L1 Head | RCAC                              |\n| Affecting the organizations Infrastructure / Application (SAP etc./ Corporate Security) | CIO / L1 Head       | RCAC                              |\n| Affecting project/engagement                                                   | BU Head             | Delivery Compliance Officer - Lead |\n\n*(Reference: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 9)*\n\n### 2. Risk Owner''s Role in Risk Treatment Plan Approval Workflow\n\nThe Risk Owner is explicitly responsible for reviewing and approving the Risk Treatment Plan.\n\n**Workflow Steps:**\n\n1.  **Risk Treatment Plan Development (Asset Class Owner''s Responsibility):**\n    *   If the organization decides to treat a risk (typically risks with a risk evaluation rating above 2), the Asset Class Owner identifies appropriate preventive, detective, and corrective controls to reduce the risk.\n    *   The Asset Class Owner determines the control rating and the residual risk value.\n    *   The **Asset Class Owner** then develops the Risk Treatment Plan, which includes a description of risks, implementation priority, proposed deadlines, and status of implementation.\n    *   The Asset Class Owner obtains approval for the Risk Treatment Plan.\n    *   *(Reference: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Treat\" and \"Risk Treatment Plan Approval\" sections; Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, section 4.7)*\n\n2.  **Risk Treatment Plan Approval (Risk Owner''s Responsibility):**\n    *   The **Risk Owner** is responsible for *reviewing and approving* the Risk Treatment Plan.\n    *   This approval is recorded on the \"Risk Assessment Template\".\n    *   *(Reference: Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Risk Treatment Plan Approval\" section; Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 - \"Risk Owner\" responsibilities, section 4.7)*\n\n### Definitions of Roles:\n\n*   **Risk Owner:** \"Person responsible for business impacted by the risk, who has accountability and authority to manage a risk.\" They are typically the heads of respective engagements (delivery or enabling functions).\n    *(Reference: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 2, section 4.4.2)*\n*   **Risk Approver:** \"Department responsible for approving risks accepted by risk owner.\"\n    *(Reference: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 2)*\n\n**Summary of Key Responsibilities (Risk Owner and Risk Approver):**\n\nThe following table summarizes the key responsibilities related to acceptance and approval roles:\n\n| Role              | Responsibility                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    |\n| :---------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Risk Owner**    | Identify asset class owner <br> Provide support and necessary resources <br> Perform cost benefit analysis and transfer risks <br> Perform cost benefit analysis and **accept risks** <br> **Review and Approve the Risk Treatment Plan** <br> Review accepted risk periodically <br> Review the Risk Assessment Periodically                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n| **Risk Approver** | **Approve the risks accepted by Risk Owner** which are not falling under risk acceptance criteria                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      |\n\n*(Reference: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3)*"','2026-02-02 05:43:45','2026-02-02 05:46:45',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(14,'984b943a638d5fddc3d4e1455ae1a0a2','TREAT risk option definition recommendation consequences cost timeline approval','"Based on the provided documents, here is the detailed information regarding the TREAT risk option:\n\n### TREAT Risk Option Definition, Recommendation, Consequences, Cost, Timeline, and Approval\n\n---\n\n### Definition\n\nThe ''Treat'' risk option involves implementing appropriate controls to reduce risks, aiming to bring down the risk evaluation rating to an acceptable level. These controls, which can be preventive, detective, and corrective, are identified to minimize the impact of respective risks arising from underlying vulnerabilities and threats. It aligns with risk reduction, mitigation, elimination, or prevention strategies by changing the likelihood or consequences of a risk.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1 Treat\n*   **Document:** ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 3.2.7 Risk Treatment (Note 1 & 3)\n\n---\n\n### Recommendation\n\nThe ''Treat'' option is recommended for:\n\n*   All risks with a **risk evaluation rating above 2**. The objective is to reduce these risks to an acceptable level (1 or 2).\n*   The Asset Class Owner is responsible for identifying appropriate preventive, detective, and corrective controls to achieve this reduction.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1 Treat\n*   **Document:** Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 (Task: Treat)\n\n---\n\n### Consequences\n\nWhen the ''Treat'' option is applied, the primary consequence is the determination of the **Residual Risk Value**.\n\n*   **Control Implementation:** Controls are identified and rated on a scale of 1 to 5 (see Control Rating table below).\n*   **Control Rating Calculation:** The Control Rating is determined using the following formula:\n    `Control Rating = FLOOR (AVERAGE (Preventive Control Rating *1, Detective Control Rating *0.75, Corrective Control Rating*0.5))`\n    *   Weightage: Preventive control (1), Detective control (0.75), Corrective control (0.5).\n*   **Residual Risk Value Calculation:** The residual risk value is the difference between the initial Risk Evaluation Rating and the Control Rating:\n    `Residual Risk value = Risk Evaluation Rating  Control Rating`\n*   **Residual Risk Range:** The Residual Risk value shall be either 1, 2, 3, 4 or 5.\n*   **Management Decision:** The calculated residual risk value triggers a management decision. If the treatment does not lead to an acceptable level of residual risks, further treatment or another iteration of the risk assessment might be required.\n*   **Monitoring Effectiveness:** Measurement metrics with trends shall be maintained to monitor the effectiveness of the implemented controls and ensure they are managed effectively.\n\n**Preventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating Definitions:**\n\n\nPreventive/Detective/Corrective Control Rating | Definition                                                                \n\n1                                              | Non-existent or has major deficiencies and do not operate as intended.    \n2                                              | Limited, high level of risk remains, significant deficiencies.            \n3                                              | Controls in place with few deficiencies in terms of medium risk issues.   \n4                                              | Designed and operating, with few deficiencies in terms of low risk issues.\n5                                              | Designed and operating, with no deficiencies.                             \n\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1 Treat, Section 4.6.5, Table 8\n*   **Document:** Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3\n*   **Document:** ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 5.1\n\n---\n\n### Cost\n\nWhile the ''Treat'' option itself does not explicitly list ''cost'' as a direct output or required field for its plan, the broader risk management framework considers cost:\n\n*   **Risk Acceptance Criteria:** Cost/benefit balance between prospective losses and the cost of controls can be a factor in defining risk acceptance criteria.\n*   **General Risk Management:** For other risk options like ''Transfer'' or ''Accept'', a cost-benefit analysis is explicitly mentioned. This implies that financial considerations are generally part of decision-making in risk management.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.4 Accept, Section 6.4.2 d)\n*   **Document:** ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 6.4.2 d)\n\n---\n\n### Timeline\n\nThe Risk Treatment Plan, which is formulated when the ''Treat'' option is chosen, must include:\n\n*   **Proposed deadlines** to start the risk treatment and the completion of risk treatment.\n*   **Implementation timeframes**.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.7 Risk Treatment Plan\n*   **Document:** ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.6.1 Formulation of the risk treatment plan\n\n---\n\n### Approval\n\nThe approval process for the ''Treat'' risk option and its associated plan involves:\n\n*   **Asset Class Owner:** Is responsible for obtaining approval for the risk treatment plan.\n*   **Risk Owner:** Is responsible for developing, reviewing, and approving the Risk Treatment Plan. The plan itself must include an explicit \"Approval from risk owner\" field. The Risk Owner also accepts the residual risks remaining after treatment.\n\n*   **Document:** Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 3 (Risk Treatment Plan Approval)\n*   **Document:** Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.7 Risk Treatment Plan, Table 3 (Roles and responsibilities)\n*   **Document:** ISO IEC 27005-2022.pdf, Section 8.6.2 Approval by risk owners, Section 8.6.3 Acceptance of the residual information security risks"','2026-02-02 05:44:47','2026-02-02 05:44:47',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(15,'a99de08cdc7e2d15ec9e7f7369ccc2a8','ACCEPT risk option definition recommendation consequences cost timeline approval','"Error searching knowledge base: 429 You exceeded your current quota, please check your plan and billing details. For more information on this error, head to: https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/rate-limits. To monitor your current usage, head to: https://ai.dev/rate-limit. \n* Quota exceeded for metric: generativelanguage.googleapis.com/generate_content_free_tier_requests, limit: 5, model: gemini-2.5-flash\nPlease retry in 9.5284237s. [links {\n  description: \"Learn more about Gemini API quotas\"\n  url: \"https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/rate-limits\"\n}\n, violations {\n  quota_metric: \"generativelanguage.googleapis.com/generate_content_free_tier_requests\"\n  quota_id: \"GenerateRequestsPerMinutePerProjectPerModel-FreeTier\"\n  quota_dimensions {\n    key: \"model\"\n    value: \"gemini-2.5-flash\"\n  }\n  quota_dimensions {\n    key: \"location\"\n    value: \"global\"\n  }\n  quota_value: 5\n}\n, retry_delay {\n  seconds: 9\n}\n]"','2026-02-02 05:44:50','2026-02-02 05:44:50',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(17,'bb9ee4b3b087acadf9dabf4236d3eb00','Risk Treatment Decision options TREAT ACCEPT TRANSFER TERMINATE definitions recommendations consequences costs timelines approvals','"Based on the provided organization documents, here is the detailed breakdown of the four Risk Treatment Decision options: **TREAT, ACCEPT, TRANSFER, and TERMINATE.**\n\n---\n\n### **1. TREAT (Mitigation)**\n\n**Definition:**\nThe process of reducing risks by implementing appropriate controls to bring the risk evaluation rating down to an acceptable level (Rating 1 or 2).\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.1*\n\n**Recommendations:**\n*   Identify a combination of **Preventive, Detective, and Corrective** controls.\n*   Controls should be rated on a scale of 1 to 5.\n*   A **Risk Treatment Plan** must be developed by the Asset Class Owner.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.1 & 4.7*\n\n**Consequences & Calculations:**\n*   **Control Rating Formula:** `FLOOR(AVERAGE(Preventive * 1, Detective * 0.75, Corrective * 0.5))`\n*   **Residual Risk Calculation:** `Risk Evaluation Rating - Control Rating`\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.1*\n\n**Costs & Timelines:**\n*   **Timelines:** The Risk Treatment Plan must include proposed deadlines for both the **start** and **completion** of treatment.\n*   **Costs:** Effectiveness is measured via metrics and trends to ensure the investment in controls is efficient.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.7*\n\n**Approvals:**\n*   **Risk Treatment Plan Approval:** Approved by the **Risk Owner**.\n*   **Consultation:** Guidance provided by **Risk & Compliance**.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management SOP, Table 3*\n\n---\n\n### **2. ACCEPT (Retention)**\n\n**Definition:**\nAn informed decision to take a particular risk. This is used for risks with a rating of 1 or 2 (Acceptable) or for risks above 2 where control implementation is not feasible due to financial, administrative, or technical reasons.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.4 & ISO/IEC 27005:2022*\n\n**Recommendations:**\n*   Perform a **Cost-Benefit Analysis** prior to the decision.\n*   Identify \"Compensating Controls\" that may be in place.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.4 & Followup template*\n\n**Consequences:**\n*   The risk is retained by the organization.\n*   If the risk is above the acceptance criteria, it must be highlighted to the Risk Owner and formally recorded in a **Risk Acceptance Form**.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management SOP, Table 3*\n\n**Timelines:**\n*   Management approval for acceptance must specify a **\"valid till\" date**.\n*   Accepted risks must be reviewed periodically (Quarterly/Annually).\n*   **Source:** *Followup template, Section 4 & Risk Transfer template*\n\n**Approvals:**\n| Impact Category | Risk Owner | Risk Approver |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Contractual Non-compliance** | CIO / Legal / L1 Head | Risk & Compliance Apex Committee (RCAC) |\n| **Infrastructure / Corp Security** | CIO / L1 Head | RCAC |\n| **Project / Engagement** | BU Head | Delivery Compliance Officer - Lead |\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Table 9*\n\n---\n\n### **3. TRANSFER (Sharing)**\n\n**Definition:**\nShifting the financial or operational impact of a risk to a third party (e.g., insurer or vendor). Ownership may partially remain, but **accountability always remains with the organization**.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Transfer template_Guidelines*\n\n**Recommendations & Methods:**\n*   **Insurance:** Cyber, liability, or professional indemnity.\n*   **Outsourcing:** Managed services.\n*   **Contracts:** SLAs, indemnity clauses, and penalty clauses.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Transfer template_Guidelines*\n\n**Consequences & Costs:**\n*   **Cost-Benefit Analysis:** Must compare the cost of insurance/contracting vs. potential loss.\n*   **Residual Risk:** Risk is never fully transferred; the organization must identify remaining exposure.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.3 & Transfer Template*\n\n**Timelines:**\n*   Must document **Transfer Start Date** (Effective date) and **Transfer End Date** (Expiry date).\n*   **Source:** *Risk Transfer template, Template Information*\n\n**Approvals:**\n*   The **Risk Owner** is responsible for performing the cost-benefit analysis and executing the transfer.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Table 3*\n\n---\n\n### **4. TERMINATE (Avoidance)**\n\n**Definition:**\nEliminating the risk by ceasing the activity, decommissioning the asset, or withdrawing from the situation that presents the risk.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Section 4.6.2 & ISO/IEC 27005:2022*\n\n**Recommendations:**\n*   Used for \"Non-Acceptable Risks\" where the risk cannot be treated or transferred.\n*   **Methods:** Asset decommissioned, process stopped, application retired, or activity discontinued.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management SOP, Table 3 & Followup template*\n\n**Consequences:**\n*   Requires confirmation that all dependencies related to the terminated process/asset are addressed.\n*   **Residual Risk Level:** Expected to be Low/Negligent after termination.\n*   **Source:** *Followup template, Section 4*\n\n**Timelines:**\n*   Must record the specific **Date of Termination / Decommissioning**.\n*   **Source:** *Followup template, Section 4*\n\n**Approvals:**\n*   **Responsibility:** The **Risk Owner** is responsible for the decision to avoid non-acceptable risks.\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management SOP, Table 3*\n\n---\n\n### **Summary of Risk Treatment Decision Criteria**\n| Risk Rating Range | Classification | Necessary Action |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **1 to 2** | Acceptable Risk | Accept / Retain the risk. |\n| **3 to 5** | Non-Acceptable Risk | Treat, Transfer, or Terminate. |\n*   **Source:** *Risk Management Guidelines v1.0, Table 7*"','2026-02-02 07:18:12','2026-02-02 12:56:34',6);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(19,'247617a52aa02f5b07c5e607d54a14c1','Risk owner roles by asset type Main Headquarters Building','"Based on the provided documents, here is the detailed information regarding risk owner roles and responsibilities related to assets such as the **Main Headquarters Building** (categorized under Buildings/Infrastructure).\n\n### 1. Risk Owner Identification for Building Assets\nAccording to the **Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx**, the organization assigns Risk Owners based on the \"Impact Coverage\" of the risk. A building asset (like the Main Headquarters Building) falls under \"Organizations Infrastructure / Corporate Security.\"\n\n| Impact Coverage | Risk Owner | Risk Approver |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Affecting the organizations Infrastructure / Application (SAP etc. / **Corporate Security**) | **CIO / L1 Head** | RCAC |\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines, Table 9 (SN 2).*\n\n### 2. Definition and General Role of the Risk Owner\nThe documents provide specific definitions for the role of a Risk Owner:\n*   **Definition:** A person or entity with the accountability and authority to manage a risk. They are responsible for the business area impacted by the risk.\n*   **Scope:** Risk owners are typically the heads of respective engagements, which include delivery or enabling functions.\n\n*Source: Asset Management SOP, Table 1; Risk Management Guidelines, Table 2 & Section 4.4.2.*\n\n### 3. Specific Responsibilities of the Risk Owner\nFor assets like the Main Headquarters Building, the **Risk Owner (CIO / L1 Head)** has the following tasks as defined in **Table 3** of the **Risk Management Guidelines**:\n\n*   **Identify Asset Class Owner:** Designate the individual or department responsible for the specific asset.\n*   **Support & Resources:** Provide necessary resources and support for risk management activities.\n*   **Risk Treatment Approval:** Review and approve the Risk Treatment Plan.\n*   **Risk Acceptance/Transfer:** \n    *   Perform cost-benefit analysis before deciding to transfer risks (e.g., to insurance).\n    *   Perform cost-benefit analysis before deciding to accept risks.\n*   **Monitoring:** Periodically review accepted risks and the overall Risk Assessment.\n*   **Communication:** Identify points of contact for business and operations to communicate or update risk status.\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.3.1 (Table 3) and Section 4.9.*\n\n### 4. Treatment of Building Assets (Insurance/Transfer)\nThe Main Headquarters Building is specifically identified as an asset eligible for risk transfer through insurance to mitigate impacts from natural disasters (fire, flood, earthquake, etc.).\n*   **Assets covered:** Building, Other plant and machinery, Computer hardware, etc.\n*   **Coverage includes:** Physical damage against fire, lightning, explosion, riot, storm, cyclone, flood, earthquake fire, and shock.\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.6.3 (Transfer).*\n\n### 5. Related Role: Asset Class Owner\nWhile the **Risk Owner** (CIO/L1 Head) is accountable for the business impact, the **Asset Class Owner** is responsible for the tactical maintenance and implementation of controls. \n\nAccording to **Table 3** of the **Risk Management Guidelines**, the Asset Class Owner''s duties for the building would include:\n*   Identifying the asset and its class.\n*   Identifying threats (e.g., Earthquake, Flood, Fire, Unauthorized physical access).\n*   Identifying associated vulnerabilities (e.g., Lack of fire-fighting equipment, lack of physical monitoring).\n*   Determining risk values and identifying appropriate treatment options (Preventive, Detective, and Corrective controls).\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.3.1 (Table 3) and Annexure A.*\n\n### 6. Asset Inventory Context\nIn the **Sample asset data_Agentic AI.xlsx**, while specific physical assets like \"Server Rack\" and \"Employee Workstations\" are listed with owners (IT Infrastructure Manager and End-User Computing respectively), the **Main Headquarters Building** is not explicitly listed in the sample inventory rows. However, the **Asset Management SOP** requires all physical assets to be categorized and assigned an **Asset Class Owner** by the Engagement Head, Function Head, or Project Head.\n\n*Source: Sample asset data_Agentic AI.xlsx; Asset Management SOP, Table 3.*"','2026-02-02 07:19:14','2026-02-02 07:24:03',2);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(21,'12763c7bf5799a5372e91eb60ead9020','Risk owner roles approval workflow asset type Corporate Security Infrastructure','"Based on the provided documents, the details regarding the risk owner roles, approval workflow, and the specific context for \"Corporate Security Infrastructure\" are as follows:\n\n### 1. Risk Owner and Approver for Corporate Security Infrastructure\nAccording to the **Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx**, specific personnel are assigned based on the impact coverage of the risk.\n\n**Table 9: Risk Ownership and Approval for Infrastructure**\n| Impact coverage | Risk Owner | Risk Approver |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Affecting the organizations Infrastructure / Application (SAP etc./ **Corporate Security**) | **CIO / L1 Head** | **RCAC** |\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.6.4 (Table 9)*\n\n---\n\n### 2. Risk Management Roles and Responsibilities\nThe roles involved in the workflow for an asset like Corporate Security Infrastructure are defined in the **Risk Management Guidelines** (Table 3) and **Asset Management SOP**:\n\n*   **Risk Owner (CIO / L1 Head for Corporate Security):**\n    *   Identifies the Asset Class Owner.\n    *   Provides support and necessary resources.\n    *   Performs cost-benefit analysis for transferring or accepting risks.\n    *   Reviews and approves the Risk Treatment Plan.\n    *   Periodically reviews accepted risks and the overall Risk Assessment.\n    *   Accountable for the business impacted by the risk and has the authority to manage it.\n\n*   **Risk Approver (RCAC for Corporate Security):**\n    *   Responsible for approving risks accepted by the Risk Owner that do not fall under the standard risk acceptance criteria (i.e., risks with a rating above 2).\n\n*   **Asset Class Owner (e.g., IT Infrastructure Manager or Cybersecurity Team Lead):**\n    *   Identifies assets, threats, and vulnerabilities.\n    *   Determines risk values and impact.\n    *   Identifies risk treatment options and residual risk.\n    *   Obtains approval for the risk treatment plan from the Risk Owner.\n    *   Communicates with stakeholders throughout the process.\n\n*   **Control Owner:**\n    *   Responsible for the implementation of specific security controls.\n    *   Provides necessary support and evidence for control effectiveness.\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines, Table 2 & Table 3; Asset Management SOP, Table 1*\n\n---\n\n### 3. Approval Workflow\nThe workflow for managing risks associated with Corporate Security Infrastructure follows a structured sequence of assessment, treatment, and formal approval.\n\n#### A. Risk Treatment Plan Approval Workflow\n1.  **Identification:** The Risk Owner identifies the Asset Class Owner.\n2.  **Assessment:** The Asset Class Owner conducts the assessment and identifies appropriate preventive, detective, and corrective controls.\n3.  **Plan Development:** The Asset Class Owner develops the Risk Treatment Plan (including description, priority, deadlines, and status).\n4.  **Guidance:** Risk & Compliance provides guidance and consultation.\n5.  **Final Approval:** The **Risk Owner** reviews and signs off on the Risk Treatment Plan.\n\n*Source: Risk Management SOP, Table 3; Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.7*\n\n#### B. Risk Acceptance Approval Workflow (For Non-Acceptable Risks)\nIf a risk rating or residual risk value is above the acceptance threshold (Rating > 2), the following workflow is triggered:\n1.  **Highlighting:** The Asset Class Owner highlights the non-acceptable risk to the Risk Owner using the Risk Assessment Template and Risk Acceptance Form.\n2.  **Decision:** The **Risk Owner** (CIO / L1 Head) decides to accept the risk (based on a cost-benefit analysis or technical/administrative feasibility).\n3.  **Formal Approval:** The **Risk Approver** (RCAC) provides the final approval for the risk accepted by the Risk Owner.\n\n*Source: Risk Management SOP, Table 3; Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.6.4*\n\n#### C. AI-Enhanced Workflow Automation\nAs per the **Agentic AI Collaboration workflow.xlsx**, the following logic is applied to the approval process:\n*   **Decision Logic Execution:** If a deadline for approval or treatment is missed, the AI agent automatically escalates the task to the next-level approver as per guidelines.\n*   **Action Automation:** The system sends escalation emails to the Risk Approver for overdue tasks and sends reminders to the Risk Owner until completion.\n*   **Evidence Collection:** If evidence is missing for a control, the AI sends a request to the Control Owner before the Risk Owner/Approver reviews the status.\n\n*Source: Agentic AI Collaboration workflow.xlsx, SHEETS: WORKFLOW and OUTLINE*\n\n---\n\n### 4. Asset Context: Corporate Security Infrastructure\nWhile \"Corporate Security\" is categorized under Infrastructure/Applications for ownership purposes, the **Sample asset data_Agentic AI.xlsx** provides examples of what constitutes these types of assets:\n\n*   **Physical Assets:** Server Racks & Networking Equipment (Central server racks, core switches).\n*   **Software Assets:** Antivirus & Endpoint Security Software (McAfee Endpoint, CrowdStrike Agent).\n*   **Service Assets:** Internet Connectivity Services (Primary fiber links).\n\n**Asset Class Owners** for these specific components (who report into the Corporate Security Risk Owner/CIO) include the **IT Infrastructure Manager**, **Cybersecurity Team Lead**, and **Network Operations Lead**.\n\n*Source: Sample asset data_Agentic AI.xlsx, Sheet: Asset inventory*"','2026-02-02 08:33:39','2026-02-02 08:33:39',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(23,'364635d1b58a6b2deee87259cd78aa2f','What fields are in the Risk Acceptance Form template?','"Based on the provided documentation, the fields for the **Risk Acceptance Form** are primarily detailed in the Excel template specifically designed for this purpose.\n\n### **1. Risk Acceptance Form Fields**\nAccording to the document **Risk Acceptance Form_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx** (Sheet: *Risk Acceptance Form*), the template contains the following fields:\n\n| Field Name | Description / Instructions |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Name of Engagement** | Identification of the specific engagement. |\n| **Name of Project** | Identification of the specific project. |\n| **Facility & Location** | Includes a sub-field for **Address**. |\n| **LOB** | Line of Business. |\n| **BU Head/DU head** | Text entry field for the Business Unit or Delivery Unit head. |\n| **L1 Head** | Text entry field for the L1 Head. |\n| **Risk ID** | Unique identifier for the risk. |\n| **Risk Category** | The classification of the risk. |\n| **Risk Description** | Detailed explanation of the identified risk. |\n| **Compensating controls** | Existing or planned controls to mitigate the risk impact. |\n| **Justification for Risk Acceptance** | The business or technical reason why the risk is being accepted rather than treated. |\n| **Risk acceptance valid till** | Expiration date for the risk acceptance. |\n| **Risk Approved by** | Defaulted to: *Risk & Compliance Apex Committee*. |\n| **Name, Designation and EmpID of Risk Approver** | Details of the individual approving the risk. |\n| **Risk Acceptance Signoff** | An attestation statement: *\"This form serves as an attestation that the Impact and risk mentioned may be allowed till < end date >\"* |\n| **Name** | Name of the person signing off. |\n| **Signature** | Signature of the signee. |\n| **Date** | Date of the signoff. |\n| **Risk Owned By** | Determined by logic (see \"Form Logic\" below). |\n| **Name, Designation and EmpID of Risk Owner** | Details of the individual owning the risk. |\n| **Name of Client CISO** | *\"This field will be populated in case of engagements, where the client approval is necessary.\"* |\n| **Approval Date & Evidence** | *\"This field will be populated in case of engagements, where the client approval is necessary.\"* |\n\n---\n\n### **2. Form Logic and Conditional Roles**\nThe document **Risk Acceptance Form_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx** contains specific logic to determine the \"Risk Owned By\" field based on who the \"Risk Approver\" is:\n\n*   **Formula found in Cell C22:**\n    `=IF(TRIM(TEXT(C15,\"\"))=\"Risk & Compliance Apex Committee\",\"CIO/Legal/L1 Head\",IF(C15=\"CISO\",\"CIO / L1 Head \",IF(C15=\"Delivery Compliance Officer\",\"BU Head\")))`\n\n**Sheet2** of the same document further clarifies the mapping of Asset Categories to Approvers and Acceptors:\n\n| Category of Assets | Risk Approver | Risk Acceptor |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Physical | IS APEX Forum | CIO/Legal/L1 Head |\n| Services | CISO | CIO / L1 Head |\n| Information | RISO | BU Head |\n| Software | | |\n| People | | |\n\n---\n\n### **3. Context from the SOP**\nAccording to the **Risk Management SOP_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx** (Table 3), the Risk Acceptance Form is used in the following procedural steps:\n\n*   **Highlighting Risk:** If a risk evaluation rating/final residual risk value is above the risk acceptance criteria, the Asset Class Owner must highlight the risk to the Risk Owner using the Risk Acceptance Form.\n*   **Acceptance:** The Risk Owner uses the form to formally accept the risk.\n*   **Approval:** The Risk Approver uses the form to provide final approval for the acceptance of the risk.\n*   **Records:** The form is categorized as a mandatory **ISMS Record** and an **Output** of the Risk Management process (Table 4).\n\n### **4. Context from Guidelines**\nThe **Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx** (Section 4.6.4) specifies that for any risk with an evaluation rating above 2 where control implementation is not feasible (financial, administrative, or technical), the Risk Owner must use this process to accept the \"non-acceptable\" risk. If the risk affects a customer engagement, an approval from the authorized customer approving authority must be obtained (captured in the \"Client CISO\" fields of the form)."','2026-02-02 09:16:19','2026-02-02 09:16:19',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(24,'f3faf0628384b95b8c510f5b18f06b22','What fields are in the Risk Transfer Form template?','"Based on the provided documents from the organization''s knowledge base, the fields included in the **Risk Transfer Form template** are detailed in the document **Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx**.\n\n### **Risk Transfer Form Template Fields**\nAccording to the \"Template information\" sheet, the form consists of the following 13 fields:\n\n| Field | Description / Expected Data |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Risk ID** | Unique risk identifier |\n| **Risk Description** | Description of the risk |\n| **Root Cause** | Cause of the risk |\n| **Inherent Risk Rating** | High / Critical |\n| **Transfer Method** | Insurance / Vendor / Contract |\n| **Third Party Name** | Insurer / Vendor |\n| **Scope of Transfer** | What is covered |\n| **Contract Reference** | Policy / Agreement ID |\n| **Transfer Start Date** | Effective date |\n| **Transfer End Date** | Expiry date |\n| **Residual Risk Rating** | Medium / Low |\n| **Risk Owner** | Internal accountable owner |\n| **Review Frequency** | Quarterly / Annually |\n\n***Source:** Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Template information*\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Context and Guidelines**\nThe \"Guidelines\" sheet within the same document provides further detail on the values and procedures associated with these fields:\n\n*   **Common Risk Transfer Methods (to populate \"Transfer Method\"):**\n    *   Insurance (e.g., cyber, liability, professional indemnity)\n    *   Outsourcing / Managed Services\n    *   Contracts & Indemnity Clauses\n    *   SLAs and Penalty Clauses\n    *   Joint ventures / partnerships\n*   **Asset Coverage Examples (for \"Scope of Transfer\"):** \n    Per the *Risk Management Guidelines*, insurance typically covers physical damage to assets such as buildings, plant and machinery, computer hardware/software, networking equipment, and furniture/fittings.\n*   **Important Procedure Requirement:** Prior to arriving at a decision to transfer a risk, a **cost-benefit analysis** must be performed (*Risk Management Guidelines, Section 4.6.3*).\n\n***Source:** Risk Transfer template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Sheet: Guidelines; Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.3*\n\n---\n\n### **Related Fields from the Follow-up Template**\nThe **Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx** includes a specific section for monitoring transferred risks (Section 4), which asks the following progress-related questions:\n*   Has the risk been transferred through insurance, outsourcing, or contract? (Yes / Partially or No)\n*   Name of third party / insurer and reference number\n*   Scope of risk transferred (Brief)\n*   Is the risk fully transferred? (Yes / Partially or No)\n*   Is residual risk still acceptable after transfer? (Yes / Partially or No)\n*   Review frequency for transferred risk (Annual / Bi-annual / Other)\n*   Evidence of Transfer available (Yes - attach reference / No)\n\n***Source:** Follow template_Use case v1.0.xlsx, Section 4: Decision-Specific Questions*"','2026-02-02 16:54:03','2026-02-02 16:55:29',1);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(25,'785207020ca87599c479c162e60be449','asset inventory structure asset identification fields asset type categories','"Based on the provided documents, the asset inventory structure, identification fields, and categorization are detailed as follows:\n\n### 1. Asset Inventory Structure\nAccording to the **Risk Assessment Template_For Agentic AI RM Use Case.xlsx (Sheet: Asset Inventory)**, the inventory is organized to capture preliminary information followed by valuation and classification. The document states:\n*   **Organization:** \"The asset inventory is populated function wise based on discussions with the asset class / function owner.\"\n*   **Process Flow:** Capture preliminary asset information  Determine Business Impact Ratings (C, I, A)  Automatically derive overall Business Value.\n\n### 2. Asset Identification Fields\nThe **Asset Management Guidelines** and the **Risk Assessment Template** specify the following fields to be captured for every asset:\n\n#### Core Identification Fields\n*(Source: Asset Management Guidelines, Section: Asset Identification; Risk Assessment Template, Sheet: Asset Inventory)*\n*   **Sno:** Serial number.\n*   **Asset Class Name / Title:** The name of the asset class.\n*   **Description:** A detailed explanation of what the asset is.\n*   **Examples:** Specific instances of the asset (e.g., \"SAP ERP\" under Software Assets).\n*   **Asset Type:** Categorization (Physical, Software, Information, Service, or People).\n*   **Asset Class Owner:** The person responsible for the maintenance and implementation of controls (**Asset Management SOP, Table 1**).\n*   **Asset Custodian:** The person or department to whom the asset is physically allocated (**Asset Management Guidelines, Table 2**).\n*   **Location:** Physical or logical site of the asset (e.g., \"Data Center  Level 3, Pune\").\n*   **Status:** The current state of the asset (e.g., production, in-stock, scrap, etc.).\n*   **License Information:** Relevant for software or service assets.\n\n#### Valuation and Classification Fields\n*(Source: Risk Assessment Template, Sheet: Asset Inventory)*\n*   **Business Impact  Confidentiality:** Rating (Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, Extreme).\n*   **Business Impact  Integrity:** Rating (Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, Extreme).\n*   **Business Impact  Availability:** Rating (Insignificant, Moderate, Serious, Extreme).\n*   **Asset Business Value:** Derived value (Very Low, Low, Medium, High, Very High).\n*   **Asset Criticality Classification:** Final classification (Insignificant, Low Critical, Medium Critical, High Critical, Very High Critical).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Asset Type Categories\nAs per **Annexure A of the Asset Management Guidelines**, assets are categorized into five broad classes:\n\n| Category | Description | Examples from Documents |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Physical Assets** | Hardware equipment to support operations, including computer and communication equipment, and facility infrastructure. | Servers, Workstations, Laptops, Routers, Switches, UPS, DG Set, Firewalls, Shredders, Safes, Cabinets. |\n| **Software Assets** | Software used for processing information, including operating systems, licenses, and development tools. | System Software (OS), Application Software (ERP), Utility Software, Software Licenses, Compilers, Database tools. |\n| **Information Assets** | Data produced, processed, or stored by the organization in physical or electronic format. | Contracts & SLAs, Source Code, Database files, HR Files, ISMS records, User manuals, Emails, KYC data. |\n| **Service Assets** | Internal or external services provided to or by the organization enabling operations. | Cloud Hosting (AWS/Azure), Internet Connectivity, Physical Security Services, IT Services, Power Supply. |\n| **People Assets** | Employees, customers, and third-party contractors considered valuable assets while in organizational custody. | System Administrators, Service Desk Support Team, Managers, Engineers, Senior Management. |\n\n---\n\n### 4. Detailed Asset Type Mapping\nThe **Asset Management Guidelines (Table 8)** provides a comprehensive list of specific types mapped to categories:\n\n| Asset Category | Asset Type (Sub-Category Examples) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Physical** | Active Directory Server, Core Switch, Desktops, HVAC, IDS/IPS, Laptops, Pen drive, UPS, Warehouses, Archives. |\n| **Software** | System Software (OS), Software License, Application Software, Utility Software, Customer Supplied software. |\n| **Information** | Contracts & SLAs, Source Code, Test Documents, Database files, User & Operational manuals, License Documents. |\n| **Services** | Physical Security Services, Data Management Services, Email Services, Communication links, Networking Services. |\n| **People** | Engineer, Lead, Managers, Senior Management. |\n\n### 5. Responsibilities for Inventory Maintenance\n*   **Identification of Asset Class Owners:** Performed by Engagement Head / Function Head / Project Head (**Asset Management SOP, Table 3**).\n*   **Inventory Creation/Categorization:** The **Asset Class Owner** is responsible for identifying, categorizing, and capturing all information in the inventory (**Asset Management SOP, Table 3**).\n*   **Review Frequency:** The inventory must be reviewed by the Asset Class Owner **at least annually**, or whenever there is a change (**Asset Management Guidelines, Section: Periodic Review**)."','2026-02-03 13:24:02','2026-02-03 13:24:02',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(26,'f2e5bc79dceadd57e080c32d3f13066e','risk assessment methodology impact probability rating scales control framework','"Based on the provided documents from the organizations knowledge base, the following details outline the risk assessment methodology, impact and probability scales, and the control framework.\n\n### 1. Risk Assessment Methodology\nThe organization follows a structured process to identify, analyze, and evaluate risks to information system assets.\n\n**Process Steps:**\n1.  **Identify Organizations Context:** Identify areas impacted and the users responsible for maintaining assets and controls.\n2.  **Identify Risk Owners:** Assign responsibility to heads of respective engagements (delivery or enabling functions).\n3.  **Identify Threats and Vulnerabilities:** Identify possible threats and weaknesses using Annexure A of the guidelines.\n4.  **Identify Risk Impact (RI):** Quantify the seriousness of a risk on a numerical scale (1-5), independent of probability.\n5.  **Identify Risk Probability (RP):** Capture the likelihood of a threat exploiting a vulnerability on a scale of 1-5.\n6.  **Derive Risk Value (RV):** Compute the value for each vulnerability/threat pair.\n7.  **Risk Evaluation Rating:** Bucket the Risk Value score into a rating of 1 to 5.\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Sections 4.4 and 4.5*\n\n---\n\n### 2. Risk Impact Rating Scale\nImpact is quantified as a numerical quantity reflecting the damage if a threat successfully exploits a vulnerability.\n\n| Impact Category | Impact Definition | Impact Rating |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Very Low** | Risk has negligible impact on business and operations | 1 |\n| **Low** | Risk does not have significant impact on business and operations | 2 |\n| **Medium** | Risk has minimum impact on business and operations | 3 |\n| **High** | Risk has serious impact on business and operations | 4 |\n| **Very High** | Risk has catastrophic impact on business and operations | 5 |\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 4*\n\n---\n\n### 3. Risk Probability Rating Scale\nProbability represents the chance of a threat exploiting an identified vulnerability.\n\n| Probability Category | Probability Definition | Probability Rating |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Very Low** | Greater than one year | 1 |\n| **Low** | Once every year | 2 |\n| **Medium** | Moderate / Medium: once every 4-6 months | 3 |\n| **High** | Major / High: once every 1-3 months | 4 |\n| **Very High** | Severe / Very high: more than once per month | 5 |\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 5*\n\n---\n\n### 4. Risk Evaluation Rating (Scoring)\nThe Risk Value (RV) score is categorized into a Risk Evaluation Rating.\n\n| Risk Rating | Risk Value Score |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| 1 | 0 to 5 |\n| 2 | 6 to 10 |\n| 3 | 11 to 15 |\n| 4 | 16 to 20 |\n| 5 | 21 to 25 |\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:** \n*   **Acceptable Risk:** Rating of 1 to 2.\n*   **Non-Acceptable Risk:** Rating of 3 to 5 (requires treatment).\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Table 6 and Table 7*\n\n---\n\n### 5. Control Framework and Residual Risk\nAll risks with a rating above 2 must be treated by implementing preventive, detective, and corrective controls.\n\n#### Control Rating Scale\nControls are rated on a scale of 1 to 5 based on their design and operation:\n*   **1:** Non-existent or major deficiencies.\n*   **2:** Limited, high level of risk remains.\n*   **3:** In place with few medium-risk deficiencies.\n*   **4:** Designed and operating with few low-risk deficiencies.\n*   **5:** Designed and operating with no deficiencies.\n\n#### Control Rating Calculation\nThe final Control Rating is weighted to prioritize proactive measures:\n*   **Preventive Control Weightage:** 1.0\n*   **Detective Control Weightage:** 0.75\n*   **Corrective Control Weightage:** 0.5\n\n**Formula:**\n`Control Rating = FLOOR (AVERAGE (Preventive Control Rating * 1, Detective Control Rating * 0.75, Corrective Control Rating * 0.5))`\n\n#### Residual Risk Calculation\nThe residual risk value determines if further management action is required.\n**Formula:**\n`Calculation of Residual Risk value = Risk Evaluation Rating  Control Rating`\n\nThe Residual Risk value will result in a score of 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5.\n\n*Source: Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx, Section 4.6.1 and Table 8*\n\n---\n\n### 6. Agentic AI Collaboration Workflow (Specific Methodology)\nFor the Agentic AI use case, the methodology is adapted into a 9-step automated/manual hybrid workflow:\n1.  **Data Collection:** Aggregate collaboration and asset data.\n2.  **Context Identification:** Detect tasks, owners, and dependencies.\n3.  **Risk Detection & Rating:** Assign ratings using the RA methodology tables.\n4.  **Impact Prediction:** Forecast business outcomes and potential increases in residual risk.\n5.  **Decision Logic Execution:** Initiate treatment if rating  threshold.\n6.  **Status Analysis:** Check for overdue items or missing evidence.\n7.  **Action Automation:** Update dashboards and send automated notifications.\n8.  **Follow-up Monitoring:** Track completion and verify evidence.\n9.  **Continuous Learning Loop:** Refine thresholds and prioritization based on historical data.\n\n*Source: Agentic AI Collaboration workflow.xlsx, Sheets: WORKFLOW and OUTLINE*"','2026-02-03 13:26:34','2026-02-03 13:26:34',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(27,'62c1dbd7b3117302e088fc3ffe54a985','Threat Vocabulary Database and common SAP ERP security threats','"Based on the provided documents from the organization''s knowledge base, the following is the detailed breakdown of the Threat Vocabulary Database and specific security threats associated with SAP ERP systems.\n\n### 1. Threat Vocabulary Database\nThe knowledge base provides a structured list of threats and their associated vulnerabilities used for risk assessment.\n\n#### **Core Threat Definitions**\n*   **Threat:** A potential cause of an unwanted incident, which may result in harm to a system or organization (*Risk Management Guidelines, Table 2*). ISO/IEC 27005 further defines it as a potential cause of an information security incident that can result in damage to a system or harm to an organization (*ISO/IEC 27005:2022, 3.1.9*).\n*   **Risk Source Types:** Human (intentional or unintentional), Environmental, and Technical (*ISO/IEC 27005:2022, 3.1.6*).\n\n#### **Detailed Threat and Vulnerability List**\nThe following table constitutes the organizations threat vocabulary database (*Risk Management Guidelines, Annexure A*):\n\n| Threat | Associated Vulnerabilities (Weaknesses) |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Electronic Sabotage and Malicious Code** | Inadequate OS hardening; Absence of latest security patches; Inadequate Anti-virus updates; Lack of awareness; Insufficient audit trails/log reviews; Inadequate user/privilege management; Lack of network access restrictions. |\n| **Unintentional failure of IT systems (HW/SW)** | Inadequate backup/restoration; Lack of capacity management/performance monitoring; Inadequate OS hardening; Inadequate version/patch management; Absence of periodic maintenance. |\n| **Unauthorized physical access / Physical theft** | Lack of restrictions on material movement or entry/exit; Inadequate physical security policy; Inadequate monitoring; Lack of protection for material in transit. |\n| **Negligent / Uninformed users** | Inadequate employee training/awareness programs; Lack of policy enforcement through NDAs or penalty clauses. |\n| **Communications Failures (Telecom/Internet/LAN)** | Inadequate redundancy/standby equipment; Lack of network management or change control; Inadequate incident reporting. |\n| **Public Utilities Failure (Power/Water)** | Lack of backup power; Inadequate monitoring; Inadequate maintenance (AMCs). |\n| **Loss of key personnel / Attrition / Poaching** | Dependence on key personnel; Inadequate succession planning; Lack of cross-functional training; Inadequate background checks. |\n| **Fire** | Absence of detection/fighting equipment; Flammable materials in server rooms; Lack of fire drills; Proximity to hazardous establishments. |\n| **Flood** | Lack of consideration for facility siting (near water bodies); Inadequate coordination with public authorities. |\n| **Earthquake** | Damage to paper records; Siting in seismic zones; Lack of BC/DR plans; Lack of preventive controls. |\n| **Storms / Wind / Lightning** | Lack of lightning arrestors/sensors; Inadequate coordination with public authorities. |\n| **Adverse Environmental Conditions** | Lack of temperature/humidity controls; Lack of maintenance/AMCs; Lack of monitoring. |\n| **Medical Emergencies** | Lack of emergency healthcare on-premises; Inadequate tie-ups with hospitals. |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Common SAP ERP Security Threats\nSpecific threats and monitoring criteria for ERP systems (specifically mentioning SAP) are identified in the \"Application Domain\" and \"Infrastructure Management Domain\" sections of the knowledge base.\n\n#### **Application-Level Threats (SAP Specific)**\nAccording to the **Measurement and monitoring of Risk** table (*Risk Management Guidelines, Table 10*), the following are critical threats to SAP and ERP environments:\n\n1.  **Segregation of Duties (SOD) Violations:**\n    *   **Threat:** Unauthorized combinations of access rights that allow a single user to perform conflicting business functions.\n    *   **Monitoring:** The organization monitors \"SOD violations in all applications (quarterly)\" including SAP.\n2.  **Unpatched Application Vulnerabilities:**\n    *   **Threat:** Exploitation of known software flaws within the SAP application.\n    *   **Monitoring:** \"Critical Vulnerabilities per application (quarterly)\" for systems including SAP.\n3.  **Privileged Access Abuse:**\n    *   **Threat:** Excessive or unauthorized use of administrative rights.\n    *   **Monitoring:** Number of delegations with privileged access per application (SAP mentioned specifically).\n4.  **Unauthorized Access and Authentication Failures:**\n    *   **Threat:** Brute force attacks or unauthorized entry into the ERP system.\n    *   **Monitoring:** Tracking \"Unsuccessful attempts of login\" and \"Unauthorized access details\" where authentication controls exist.\n\n#### **Data and Information Threats**\n*   **Asset Discrepancies:** A specific threat identified is the \"Discrepancy between IT asset and Asset extract from SAP/ERP system\" (*Risk Management Guidelines, Table 10*). This indicates a risk to the integrity of asset management data.\n*   **Data Leakage:** For information assets like Financial Reports (often generated by SAP), the organization maps the risk to **A.8.12 Data Leakage Prevention** and **A.8.11 Data Masking** to prevent unauthorized exposure of sensitive finance data (*ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx, Sample asset controls*).\n\n#### **Infrastructure and Configuration Threats**\n*   **Insecure Configuration:** ERP applications are subject to **A.8.9 Configuration Management** to ensure they are securely configured against unauthorized changes (*ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx, Sample asset controls*).\n*   **Unapproved Changes:** SAP environments face risks from unauthorized updates or patches. This is mitigated through **A.8.10 Change Management** and ITGC domains like \"Program Change Management\" which includes \"Segregation of development and production\" and \"Emergency change management\" (*ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx, ITGC Controls*).\n\n### 3. Supply Chain Threats (NIST RMF Perspective)\nFor organizations following the Risk Management Framework, additional threats to ERP systems arise from the supply cycle (*NIST SP 800-37, Rev 2, Executive Summary*):\n*   **Untrustworthy suppliers** providing ERP components.\n*   **Insertion of malicious code** into software updates.\n*   **Tampering** with system elements.\n*   **Insertion of counterfeits** into the hardware infrastructure supporting the ERP."','2026-02-03 13:42:55','2026-02-03 13:42:55',0);
INSERT INTO rag_cache VALUES(28,'148c90656e6266277f1c4944ec774b12','What is the Threat Vulnerability Database? What threats are documented?','"Based on the provided documentation, there is no specific entity explicitly named \"Threat Vulnerability Database.\" However, the organization maintains a comprehensive repository of threats and their associated weaknesses in **Annexure A  List of Threats and Vulnerabilities**, which is part of the **Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx**.\n\n### **What is the List of Threats and Vulnerabilities (Annexure A)?**\nAccording to the **Risk Management Guidelines (Section 4.4.3 and 4.4.4)**, this annexure serves as the official reference for personnel conducting risk assessments. It is used to:\n*   **Identify Threats:** Personnel use the list to identify various possible threats for a specific asset class.\n*   **Identify Vulnerabilities:** Personnel use the list to identify specific weaknesses that could be exploited by those threats.\n\n---\n\n### **Documented Threats and Associated Vulnerabilities**\nThe following threats and their associated vulnerabilities are documented in **Table 11 (Annexure A)** of the **Risk Management Guidelines_For RM Agentic AI Use Case v1.0.docx**:\n\n| Threat | Associated Vulnerabilities |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Earthquake** | - Unavailability / Damage to critical information on paper<br>- Lack of consideration towards siting of facility and avoidance of areas susceptible to seismic activity (e.g., Seismic Zone 4)<br>- Lack of adequate business continuity and disaster recovery plan<br>- Lack of procedures to contact external authorities<br>- Lack of preventive controls, evacuation practices, or Site Risk Assessments. |\n| **Flood** | - Lack of consideration towards siting of facility (near water bodies)<br>- Inadequate procedures for coordination with public authorities<br>- Lack of adequate business continuity and disaster recovery plan. |\n| **Fire** | - Absence of detection/firefighting equipment (extinguishers, sprinklers, smoke detectors)<br>- Presence of flammable materials (stationary, cardboard) in premises or server rooms<br>- Lack of fire drills, evacuation procedures, or equipment inspection<br>- Proximity to hazardous establishments (fuel depots, gas stations)<br>- Malfunctioning fire suppression or alerting systems. |\n| **Storms / Wind / Lightning** | - Inadequate control measures (lack of lightning arrestors and sensors)<br>- Inadequate coordination with public authorities<br>- Lack of adequate business continuity and disaster recovery plan. |\n| **Adverse Environmental Conditions** | - Lack of environmental controls (temperature and humidity)<br>- Lack of adequate maintenance procedures (e.g., AMCs)<br>- Lack of monitoring procedures. |\n| **Public Utilities Failure (Power/Water)** | - Lack of adequate backup power supply measures<br>- Inadequate monitoring, incident reporting, or maintenance procedures<br>- Lack of adequate business continuity plan. |\n| **Communications Failures (Telecom/Internet/LAN)** | - Inadequate redundancy (standby equipment/alternate providers)<br>- Inadequate monitoring, network management, or change control procedures<br>- Inadequate incident reporting, access control, or business continuity planning. |\n| **Unintentional failure of IT systems (Hardware/Software)** | - Inadequate backup/restoration or capacity management<br>- Inadequate OS hardening or version/configuration control<br>- Inadequate change/patch management or incident reporting<br>- Absence of periodic maintenance and accessible documentation. |\n| **Electronic Sabotage and Malicious Code** | - Inadequate OS hardening or absence of latest security patches<br>- Inadequate Anti-virus updates or security awareness<br>- Insufficient audit trails/log reviews<br>- Absence of restrictions on removable media<br>- Inadequate user/privilege management or password controls. |\n| **Medical Emergencies** | - Lack of emergency health care on premises<br>- Inadequate tie-ups with hospitals. |\n| **Unauthorized Physical Access / Physical Theft** | - Lack of restrictions on material movement or physical entry/exit<br>- Inadequate physical security policy or monitoring<br>- Lack of awareness or protection of material in transit<br>- Risks associated with sharing a building with other companies. |\n| **Loss of key personnel / Attrition / Poaching** | - Dependence on key personnel<br>- Inadequate succession planning or knowledge management<br>- Lack of cross-functional training<br>- Inadequate background checks. |\n| **Negligent / Uninformed Users** | - Inadequate employee training or awareness programs<br>- Lack of enforcement of policy through NDAs or penalty clauses. |\n\n### **Additional Context on Threat Management**\nAccording to the **ITGC & ISO 27001 Controls file.xlsx (Sheet: ISO 27001 Controls)**, the organization also utilizes specific controls to manage threats:\n*   **A.5.7 Threat Intelligence:** Focuses on monitoring and gathering information regarding threats.\n*   **A.8.8 Management of Technical Vulnerabilities:** Specifically addresses the lifecycle of managing vulnerabilities through patching and remediation.\n*   **A.8.7 Protection Against Malware:** Maps directly to software assets (Antivirus/endpoint security) to mitigate malicious code threats."','2026-02-03 13:49:47','2026-02-03 13:49:47',0);
